scComment: Laird's always been a natural scorer, averaging over 93 for five seasons straight as a defender before making the switch to the midfield in mid-2020. Since then (a 48-game sample), he's averaged 122 and finished 2022 as good as anyone in SuperCoach. It's hard to see him slowing down, given his age (still under 30), his elite tackling numbers (number two in the comp), ability to avoid the tag (teams opted to tag the more damaging Dawson when playing the Crows), consistency (lowest score of 93 last year with 13 games over 120) and the fact the Crows have opted to recruit players outside the midfield in recent years, meaning his full time midfield role should remain. The limited trades make SuperCoach a different game to Fantasy, where I'm more prepared to pay a 'full' price for starting selection I think will be a top scorer as I'm going to need to trade them in at one point anyway. Last year, I started with Jack Macrae who was priced at 128, more than Laird this year. That means I'm considering Laird in my starting line-up, it all depends on how many players with upside I want in my team as I typically prioritise upside over consistency in my fantasy teams.
scShort: Averaged 122 since midfield move and hard to see that changing

scComment: Brayshaw's is a player who is better in real life than his SuperCoach scoring suggests. He was top 4 in the Brownlow and won the player MVP, however he averaged the 12th most SuperCoach points amongst midfielders. This is largely to the fact he's not much of a contested footballer, despite his one percenters and effort. He wins 32% of his possessions contested (the top 8 mids averaged 47%) and averaged less than 4 clearances per game (Oliver, Miller, Laird and Neale are all 7.6). Contested possessions and clearances are gold in SuperCoach and coupled with the fact Brayshaw is clearly Fremantle's best midfielder, meaning he's subject to a tag most weeks, he's not a safe SuperCoach selection as he would appear to be from the outside. He's 23, they've added O'Meara and his TOG should increase a bit, so there's every chance Brayshaw will improve again. However, I doubt that will be enough for him to join the top 8.
scShort: His surprisingly low clearance and contested possession game, coupled with the tag threat, limits him from being a top liner in SuperCoach

scComment: Oliver is my type of Fantasy midfielder. High game time (86%), high CBAs (87%) and always around the ball (averaged over 31 touches per game in 2021 and 32 in 2022), meaning he's been a SuperCoach stud for the majority of his career. Before last season, opposition teams put more attention into Petracca, which meant Oliver avoided the tag. However, the pendulum shifted in 2022 and Oliver copped his fair share of opposition attention. However, his elite tackle rate (5.5 per game compared with 5.3 of the other top 8 mids) and contested game (54% v 47%) means he can still score fine with a tag. With the other top liners also subject to a tag this year, Oliver is likely to be the top player in SuperCoach again in 2023.
scShort: Ball magnet with a high contested rate (54%) means he's likely to be the top player in SuperCoach again in 2023

scComment: Mills continued his breakout 2021 form last season and finished the year as a top 8 averaging midfielder. He possesses a high mark and tackle game and uses the ball well, averaging 4% better disposal efficiency and 1 less clanger a game compared to the other top 8 mids. However, he clearly has the lowest CBAs when compared to this group, due to his versaltility. There were many occasions last season when he was shifted to be loose man in defence or to a wing and play behind the ball. His CBAs dropped (65% pre bye and 42% post) which coincided with a decrease in scoring (122 to 111). I have him as a top 8 mid again this season, however I'd want to be confident of him sustaining 65%+ CBAs before taking the jump.
scShort: Marks/tackles/kicking efficiency tick! Versatility and potential to be push behind the ball the concern

scComment: Steele had a disappointing SuperCoach season after coming in as the second most expensive player in the comp. He averaged an absurd 136 post bye in 2021, meaning a lot of coaches paid up thinking he was a lock as a top 4 mid. However, he never got going. Steele hurt his AC joint in Round 9, which didn't help his cause, and he never found the same levels as he did in 2021. Steele's rise to the SuperCoach elite coincided with Ratten taking over as coach and relinquishing him of his tagging duties, which saw him average 121 in 2020 and 126 in 2021. It will be interesting to see what role Ross Lyon has for him, but it is hard to see Steele not being their primary inside midfielder again. A prime bounce-back candidate and someone priced outside the top 8 mids with the ability to finish inside.
scShort: Primed for a bounce-back, as long as the new coach keeps him in his role

scComment: Docherty's return in 2021 was one of the stories of the year. SuperCoach-wise, he went from looking like not playing at all to a clear top 6 defender, averaging 110 points per game. His scoring ability isn't a shock, considering he has a career best year of 115 pre knee injuries. His issues in the past from a SuperCoach perspective have been his health and attention from opposition players. If last year was anything to go by, he looks in full fitness and teams opted to tag Saad more than Docherty, which is great for Docherty's Fantasy prospects. He doesn't get the intercept marks and possessions that the other top defenders in SuperCoach do, however he finished the season playing as an inside mid, purely due to the injuries to Carlton's regular midfielders, and showed a tackle and ball winning ability that suggest he could be in the Laird/Mills mould of Fantasy defenders turned midfielders. It's more likely he'll return to defence where he'll still likely be a top 6 defender in SuperCoach again.

Miller's progression in the last three seasons is pretty remarkable. Played as a defensive mid in 2020, to an offensive mid in 2021 to then the mid who got tagged in 2022. The added attention meant an increase in contested possessions, from 39% in 2021 to 54% in 2022. There is no harder working midfielder in the comp, and those contested numbers meant he managed to still put up some decent scores when tagged. The hope is that Anderson and Rowell take the next step in 2023 which might see Miller avoid the tag. Regardless, he's a lock for a top 8 mid for the 3rd year in a row.
scShort: Contested rate up to 57% means he'll remain a lock to be a top 8 mid for the third year in a row, despite the added attention

scComment: We know Dunkley can score as well as any player in SuperCoach. He averaged 118 in the last five games of 2018, 124 after Round 6 in 2019 and 116 in the first half of 2021. However, he's just never put together a full season, largely due to Bevo taking him out of the midfield. He had a strong 2022, averaging 109, with just 51% CBAs. Two things have gone in Dunkley's favour for 2023. First, he played enough forward to be gifted forward status in SuperCoach. The second is he's been traded to the Lions, where it's expected he'll take up a full-time midfield role. So while he comes into the season as the most expensive forward available, he certainly has some upside on his price and will very likely be the number 1 forward for the season.
scShort: Forward status + Brisbane trade makes him clearly the number 1 forward as he can score as well as any in SuperCoach

scComment: Zach Merrett isn't your typical elite SuperCoach mid. He has a low contested possession rate of 32% (compared to the other top 8 mids of 47%), however his kicking efficiency, arguably the best short kick in the competition, helps him produce top 8 numbers. He had a slow start to 2022 after an early season syndesmosis which he took a while getting back to his best. He had a role change where he started a lot of centre bounces at half forward and worked up to the ball. This saw his CBAs drop from 80% in 2021 to 61% at the bye in 2022. Not sure whether it was a planned switch or forced given Parish went down injured, but Merrett returned to Essendon's prime centre bounce mid post byes, bumping his CBAs up to 72%. He averaged 117 in this time which is more reflective of his career output. He's always been subject and vulnerable to a tag, but when playing inside he's an automatic 110+. This means he's slightly underpriced heading into 2023 and assuming Brad Scott keeps him as an inside mid.
scShort: 117 post bye when his CBAs returned to normal

scComment: Neale came into 2022 as an underpriced premium following a 2021 season where nothing went right (calf, back and ankle injuries). It was an easy selection and looked like a great one, when he averaged 130 in the first half of the season and showed 2020 was no fluke. The issue with Neale is that he is clearly Brisbane's most damaging midfielder and teams quickly learnt that if they shut down Neale, they would shut down the Lions. This saw him averaged 110 for the second half of the season. He's a much improved footballer and his high contested rate (54%) and disposal efficiency (70%) means that he can score as well as any in SuperCoach if let run free. The recruitment of Josh Dunkley should improve the Lions' midfield depth and we might see Neale run free more in 2023, and while I think it will be hard for him to match his 123 average in 2021, I still think he'll be a top 8 mid.
scShort: 54% contested into 70% effective means he'll produce top 8 numbers, despite the constant tag threat

scComment: Crouch had a much improved second season at St Kilda, averaging over 27 touches per game on just 62% CBAs. This saw him average the 8th most points amongst midfielders in AFL Fantasy and only 1 less possession than the top 8 midfielders in SuperCoach, however he ranked 20th for SuperCoach points. This is due to his low disposal efficiency, high clangers and moderate contested breakdown. It's been a habit over his career, highlighted in 2019 when he averaged 108 AFL Fantasy points and just 98 SuperCoach. His game isn't conducive to SuperCoach scoring and for that reason I can't have him in my team.
scShort: Always been a better in Fantasy than SuperCoach and unless Ross Lyon gives him 80% CBAs, it's hard to see that changing

scComment: Bailey Smith started 2022 as hot as anyone, playing an unprecedented time on ground while getting decent CBAs in a stacked Bulldog midfield. His season then derailed after being suspended for headbutting Zach Tuohy and then a club-imposed suspension saw him miss 5 of the next 6 weeks. He never hit the early season heights when he returned. However, his SuperCoach scoring, even in the early season form, was never elite numbers due to his very low contested possession rate (29% v top 8 mids of 47%) and disposal efficiency (65% v 70%). He might get a CBA boost with Dunkley leaving which may lead to a bump in contested possessions, however it's hard to see it changing enough for him to join the top 8 mid discussion.
scShort: Mights get a boost with Dunkley out, but 29% contested and 65% efficiency, he'll need a very big boost to be relevant

scComment: Macrae has been the most prolific SuperCoach scorer of the last five years and came into 2022 as the most expensive player. When he's up and about and in the right role, there are few better. However, he looked a shadow of himself last season as his CBAs reduced to 64%, down from 78% in 2021. Dunkley leaving opens up an obvious spot in the midfield. However, the Dogs' preferred midfield mix has been Libba, Bont and Smith, so Macrae's not certain to pick up the extra inside minutes. He's a big preseason watch and if he gets his CBAs back to the mid-70s, he could be the perfect discount uber premium we are hunting for as our M1/M2. However, if he takes Hunter's spot on a wing, we can no longer count him as a safe 120 midfielder.
scShort: Hopefully takes Dunkley's extra inside time and gets his CBAs up from his 5-year low in 2022 and return to be a SuperCoach uber premium

scComment: After bursting onto the scene 4 years ago, averaging 87, 101 and 117, Walsh finally had his first underwhelming season, averaging 111. There were a few factors for the regression. He returned early from a preseason syndesmosis injury where he was initially meant to miss the first 4 games and, like we saw with Zach Merrett, took a while to look back to his best. He also lost inside minutes following the recruitment of George Hewett and Adam Cerra, down from 67% CBAs in 2021 to 55% in 2022. A full preseason should fix the first issue, however Carlton still have a stacked midfield and Walsh is more suited to the wing than Cripps, Hewett and Matt Kennedy. There's enough proof over the past 5 years that to be an elite Fantasy midfielder, the CBAs need to be above 65%, so Walsh's role in the preseason will be a big watch for me. His low contested rate (35%) and tackles (3.3) will always hold him back unless he gets more time inside. If he looks like their first-choice on-baller with 70% CBAs, he's a shot to break through the 120 barrier and become a top line SuperCoach mid. If he stays on the wing, I don't think he'll get the tackle opportunities to get the big scores needed from your gun mids. He's now had offseason surgery and will miss the start of the season, ruling him out of calculations.
scShort: Preseason syndesmosis and extra mids saw him regress for the first time in 2022, will need to bump his CBAs to 70%+ to get his contested rate and tackles up and push the top 8

scComment: Gawn has been on a steady SuperCoach decline since averaging 140 in 2020, dropping 19 points in 2021 and a further 6 in 2022. It's been a mixture of a few things. He's still been the number 1 ruck in SuperCoach during this time, so it has a lot to do with the ruck role with the reduced stoppages and ruck influence since the introduction of the stand rule. He's also given up CBAs to up-and-coming ruck, Luke Jackson, from 93% in 2020 to just 66% in 2022. The good news is Jackson is gone. The bad news is Melbourne now have the fellow best SuperCoach ruck of the last decade, Brodie Grundy. This makes Gawn (and Grundy's) Fantasy prospects incredibly difficult to predict. Regardless, it's hard to see him bumping his CBAs up much from the 66% and despite being priced as cheap as he's been in 5 seasons, I'd need to see a few rounds of the Gawn/Grundy combination before being sure he's going to be the number 1 ruck in SuperCoach again.
scShort: Need to see what his role is with Grundy before being sure he's going to be the number 1 ruck in SuperCoach again

scComment: We don't often come across a 8th year breakout, but Jack Sinclair did just that in 2022. After switching to defence in 2021, he took greater rebounding responsibilities in 2022 and increased his average by a massive 27 points to 114, making him the number 1 defender in SuperCoach and earning All Australian honours. He scoring appears sustainable, averaging 5 more disposals than the top 6 defenders at better efficiency and contested rate. The only times he looked vulnerable were when the tag came, which happened a bit in the second half of the season, however his scoring still remained. There was a clear direction and desire to get the ball in his hands and this is a risk given there has been a change of coach. However from what I saw last year I find it hard to see him not scoring enough to be a top 6 defender again, regardless of the role Ross Lyon gives him.
scShort: An 8th season breakout and despite the risk of a new coach, it's hard to see him not being a top 3 defender again

scComment: I had been waiting to see what McCluggage would produce SuperCoach wise once moved inside from his customary wing role, given he played inside when he was in juniors and averaged more points than Tim Taranto and Andrew McGrath. We saw that in 2022 with a career high 55% CBAs, however it didn't reflect in his scoring as he still averaged less disposals, contested % and effective % than the top 8 mids. I've got a rule that I want my SuperCoach midfielders to take the bulk of the CBAs, and McCluggage doesn't fit that bill, even with the increase of CBAs. If anything, it's likely he'll reduce again and move back to a wing following the recruitment of Josh Dunkley and the Lions' want to give Zac Bailey and Cam Rayner more of a run in there. At age 25, he should be reaching his peak and there's still natural improvement in him, however, it's hard to see McCluggage improving to the 115 mark which you'd need him to do to be a worthwhile pick in SuperCoach.
scShort: Less disposals, contested % and effective % than the top 8 mids and hard to see that changing with the likely CBA reducing with Dunkley arriving

scComment: Petracca had an inconsistent season after a dominant 2021. He had excuses, none greater than his 10-possession game in Round 11 where he scored just 53 points after having the flu all week. He was said to have carried a sore knee for the majority of the season and was tagged in a few matches. While there is upside if he can have a healthy season, the tag threat will always be there and the fact he last lower disposals, contested rate, efficiency and tackles than the top 8 mids, he's too inconsistent for me to start with as there's a good chance he'll be available cheaper at one point during the season.
scShort: Had excuses last season which explained the drop, but his lower-than-the-top-8 disposals, tackles and efficiency beings inconsistency the other top mids don't have

scComment: Cripps' 2022 season is exactly what we're trying to look for in our starting squad and what you need to contend. Came in priced at 84 after battling back and groin issues in 2021 and well down from his career high 119 in 2018. He looked back to his best in the preseason with a 157 in the AAMI and delivered for owners, averaging 111 for the season and 115 excluding his injured game. However, he's now priced at 111 and while he's a chance to be a top 8 mid, I'd rather start with one I'm either certain will be or priced lower for the upside.
scShort: Averaged 115 excluding his injured game which is enough to make him a top 8 mid, however I feel it's a year too late for a starting pick

scComment: After a disappointing 2021 when he spent far too much time forward (50%) and sharing the ruck role with Stef Martin, English broke out in 2022 and returned to his trajectory of the great SuperCoach rucks in the game. In his 4th season, English averaged 101. At the same stage of their careers, Gawn (102) and Grundy (96) were around a similar mark. In their 7th season, Gawn averaged 111 and Grundy 130. Heading into his 7th season and with Stef Martin retired, everything is set for English to improve again. The fact we don't know how Gawn and Grundy will work together means he's the safest pick to be the number 1 ruck in SuperCoach this season. And if he can boost his average up to the 115 mark, which he showed he could do early in 2022, then he'll prove a great starting R1 option.
scShort: An early choice for the number 1 ruck with Stef gone and Gawn playing with Grundy

scComment: After romping home in 2021 averaging 111 in the second half of the season from 64% CBAs (from 33% in the first half), I had Kelly pegged to return to top 8 mid calculations in 2022. The risk that was flagged was how deep the Giants were in their midfield, with Hopper, Ward, Taranto, Kelly, Green and Coniglio all demanding time. He was a victim of this and he saw his CBAs reduce to 46% for the season and 35% post bye (c'mon Leon). However, I haven't given up hope and maybe we were just a year early. Leon is now gone so hopefully we'll see more consistency in the Giants' midfield rotation and with Hopper and Taranto also gone, there are less mouths to feed. Their starting midfield should be Green, Kelly and Coniglio. More CBAs should lead to a bump in contested possessions (currently 34% compared to the top 8 mids of 45%), tackles and disposals (both also down on the top 8). If we see Kelly hit 65%+ CBAs in the preseason (something that hasn't happened since CBAs have been public), then I'd be keen on starting with him.
scShort: No Leon, Hopper or Taranto which gives hope of seeing Kelly hit 65%+ CBAs and the 115 average we know he can produce in the right role

scComment: Dawson arrived at Adelaide having shown glimpses of being a SuperCoach stud, including averaging 116 in the NEAFL and 110 in the second half of 2021, including a 158 late in the year. However, he took his game to another level at the Crows, averaging 110 for the season and 114 post-byes, making him a clear top 6 defender. He was equally impressive in real life, using his damaging kicking skills, versatility and running power to great effect. He was so impactful that he regularly received some attention from opposition forwards. This is the only risk with Dawson heading into 2023, however his versatility meant he was thrown around a bit when tagged and there was no better effort than his 10 tackle effort in Round 17 when tagged by Maginness. It's my only hesitation starting with him as there's a chance he comes in cheaper after a tag-affected game, but it's hard to see him not being a top 6 defender again and a safe starting pick.
scShort: Watch for more attention following a brilliant 2022, but hard to see him not being a top 6 defender again

scComment: The Bont has always been a player of contention amongst SuperCoachers, given his ability to get large boosts in scores from minimal possessions. However, where you look at his stats breakdown (above the top 8 average for efficiency, contested rate, clangers, tackles, goals and goal assists), you can easily see why he's such a beast in SuperCoach. With the Dogs' stacked midfield, Bruce out and an adductor concern, Bont saw more forward time again in 2022, enough to see him gain forward status during the season and his CBAs dropped to 58%. However, Dunkley leaving and Bruce back could open up more inside minutes for Bont in 2023. That should bring extra possessions which is the area he lagged the other top 8 mids (23 v 28). If he can get that up to 27 which is was in 2021, he could challenge to be the best scorer in SuperCoach.
scShort: A stacked midfield and sore adductor kept him to 58% CBAs in 2022 and still managed 117. With Bruce back and no Dunkley he'll spend more time inside and could be a top scorer in SuperCoach

scComment: After a breakout 2021, Parish had a disappointing 2022 which saw him play just 16 games due to calf issues. He started the season strong, averaging 118, the same score he averaged in the first half of 2021, but averaged just 95 post bye as the calf issues kicked in. I've seen enough from those positive stretches to be confident Parish has the attributes to be a top-line SuperCoach asset when fully fit and in the right role. There is always a risk of the magnets changing when a new coach comes in and we've seen in 2020 (87 from 48% CBAs) and the second half of 2022 (95 from 68% CBAs) that Parish needs to have 80% CBAs to score. If it's looking that way in the preseason, then he's a valid starting option and I doubt his ownership will be much more than 5%.
scShort: Hampered by calf issues in 2022, if Scott keeps him at 80% CBAs he could be a unique top 8 mid

scComment: There hasn't been many more up and down performer in Fantasy than Angus Brayshaw. He averaged 116 in the last 4 games of 2018 playing as a pure mid. He was pushed out of the midfield for the likes of Viney, Oliver and Petracca and reduced his average by 24 across 3 seasons and found himself averaging 71 in a defensive wing role for their premiership side. Despite his low possession game, the importance of his role was highlighted by many Dees' players and fans and I was certain that this non-relevant Fantasy role would continue. However, he found himself playing in defence in 2022 following Salem's injury and excelled, averaging around the 100 mark in that role. He was then thrusted into the midfield towards the end of the season, with 53% CBAs in the last 5 and a 111 average. He comes into 2023 with defender status, which immediately makes him relevantas he has 10 points upside on his price. All about role, so keep on the preseason watch.
scShort: 111 in last 5 when back in the midfield would make him a top 6 defender, preseason role watch

scComment: His 104 average doesn't reflect it, but Luke Parker had a very good season in 2022. He was given forward status during the season which made him even more relevant and he proved to be a top 6 forward in the run home. However, he's now just a mid-only, and while he's still going as hard as ever at age 30, he's not likely to boost his score enough to be close to the top 8 mids. Let's hope he gets forward status again during the year as he would certainly be a top 6 forward again.
scShort: Now just mid-only and not likely to challenge the top 8 mids

scComment: Cogs returned to the midfield and form in 2022, following a disappointing 2021 where he averaged 60 from just 36% CBAs. He's still yet to recapture his absolute best form, which saw him average 109 twice (in 2018 and 2019 if you exclude his injured score of 0). The drop in form could be put down to a number of things: added pressure from captaincy, less stoppages where he used to rely on high tackle numbers and the depth of the Giants' midfield group, forcing Cogs to spend a lot more time forward. With the departure of Hopper and Taranto, the 3rd reason will hopefully be fixed and we'll see Cogs return to a 70%+ CBA midfielder. The concern is the new coach as we don't know what role Cogs will play and how fantasy-friendly the game-style will be. If Tigers are anything to go by, we might see less high-possession football from the Giants in 2023. The fact Cogs has forward status this season means he's always going to be on the radar, but I'd want confirmation of CBAs and game style before taking the punt on him, so he's not a starting option for me.
scShort: Forward status is handy, as is Hopper and Taranto leaving, I just need to see confirmation of role and new game-style under Kingsley

scComment: A key opportunity for a breakout is when a player moves clubs and is both reinvigorated and plays in a new role. Hewett did just that in 2022 where he relished his role as Carlton's pure inside mid, seeing 73% CBAs compared to the 28% and 33% he was at Sydney the prior 2 seasons. His role was perfectly suited to SuperCoach scoring, often winning the first possession and distributing via hands, meaning he had high contested and disposal efficiency rates. He had a career best 111, well up from his prior PB of 88. Now he's a mid-only, he's not an attractive prospect. Best case he might match his 2022 output and at his price, and that won't be enough to be a top 8 mid.
scShort: Hard to see him improving, or even matching his 2022 output, as good as his season was

scComment: Drafted as a pure outside wingman, Anderson was introduced to the CBAs at the end of 2020 and increased ever since, attending a career high 72% of Gold Coast's stoppages across the season. Players with an outside background who move inside prove great Fantasy prototypes, as they know how to spread and win the ball in space and learn to tackle and add extra disposals to boost their score. He proved he's a 110+ mid as he averaged that post bye, despite averaging less disposals, lower efficiency, lower contested, more clangers and less tackles than the top 8 mids. Heading into his 4th season, he's entering his peak and hopefully improve in some of those metrics. If so, his upside could be enough to be a viable starting squad selection.
scShort: Averaged 110 post bye despite less disposals, lower efficiency, lower contested, more clangers and less tackles than the top 8 mids

scComment: A philosophy I live by is more CBAs = more SuperCoach points. This certainly wasn't the case with Short who was moved into the Tigers' midfield in Round 7. Up until then, he was averaging 106. After Round 7, he averaged 93. The designated kicker lost a lot of the easy +6s he relied on when playing half back plus the extra kick-ins. The Richmond style forward of centre is to move it forward at all costs, which didn't suit Short's game. He's now only available as a midfielder and there's no chance of him producing scores to be a relevant midfield option. With the additions of Hopper and Taranto, I'd be very surprised if he doesn't return to half back and be available as a defender at one point. We know he can produce top 6 defender numbers. But until then, he doesn't make a good starting midfield pick.
scShort: More CBAs doesn't = more SuperCoach points for Short and unless he moves back to defence, he's unlikely to feature in Fantasy teams this year

scComment: Wines had a disappointing 2022, dropping 8 points per game from his Brownlow winning 2021. He did have excuses in 2022, none more so that the game he got subbed out prior to half time on 36. With Butters and Rozee improving and seeing more mid-time, Wines' 110 days may be over, but the 117 he averaged in his last 5 games shows he's still capable and if injury free, he could be a top 8 mid again.
scShort: No longer the main man with Butters and Rozee improving but he 117 he averaged in his last 5 games shows he still capable

scComment: After a breakout 2021, Keays looks like he was going to continue being a premium Fantasy midfielder when he averaged 114 in the first half of the season from 80% CBAs (the same amount as 2021 when he averaged 103). He ticked a lot of boxes - high CBAs, avoided the tag and did all the hard things. However, there was a clear role change midseason and Keays spent a lot of time forward, often as a negating forward, reducing his CBAs to 55% and 34% in the last 5 games. His scoring suffered, reducing his average to 82 and 71 respectively. It coincided with Sam Berry's increase in the middle, up from 52% in the first half to 76% in the second and 83% in the last 5. Berry has been earmarked as the Crows' future star midfielder and I expect Berry to keep his prominent onball position. This means Keays' role is uncertain and while we know he can produce 108+ in the right role, I'm not confident enough in that role happening.
scShort: Sam Berry took his inside role post bye and reduced Keays to 34% CBAs and 713 points in the last 5 games. That might continue in 2023.

scComment: Amon finds himself at the Hawks after back-to-back 92 seasons playing on a wing at Port. Wingmen struggle in SuperCoach given the weighted scoring towards contested possessions and clearances, of which Amon has a contested rate of 23% (compared to the top 8 mids of 45%). I need my SuperCoach mids to get 65%+ CBAs to help with scoring and consistency and unless Amon plays as that for his new team (which I doubt), he won't be on my radar.
scShort: Career high of 92 from a 23% contested rate is why wingmen aren't great SuperCoach options

scComment: Treloar has been a Fantasy stud over the journey and has one of the best career Fantasy averages in the league, but he's been restricted by soft tissue injuries for a few years now. He only missed the one game in 2022, after missing 19 the two years prior, but was subbed out of another one and never looked his explosive best. He used to have the perfect balance on inside and outside where he would win the ball in the contest and spread hard outside for easy marks to be that 110 player we crave. I feel like that is now behind him and he's more of a 100-guy. What may impact that is role, as Treloar was used through the midfield, forward and in defence in 2022, even taking kick-ins at the end of the season. If he's available anywhere outside the midfield then he'll be in consideration given he's been one of the best ball winners in the comp for a few years now, but as a mid-only, I think there are safer options with greater upside.
scShort: Soft tissue concerns for over 4 years now and seems to be more off a 95/100-guy than the 110 stud of the past

scComment: Viney is a pure inside midfielder and a gun in real life, but doesn't get enough easy ball. Add in the fact he goes at 65% efficiency and 5 clangers a game, you can see why his career best SuperCoach season is 101. That's not enough to consider.
scShort: Too inside to ever be much more than a 100-guy

scComment: If it weren't for Docherty, Sicily's 2022 would be the story of the year. After missing 2021 with an ACL, Sicily had a career best season, averaging 113 points per game on the back of league leading marks and rebounds and top 10 1%ers, spoils, intercepts and kicks. He proved a bargain buy given his 30% discount for missing the full season and a good learning experience to know that with modern sports science, players can return at an elite level following an ACL (we saw the same with Witts last season). The Hawks are in total development mode which means a few things for Sicily's 2023 prospects. They aren't going to win many games, meaning the ball will be in the backline a lot, with plenty of kick-in opportunities. Sicily averaged 118 in losses compared to 106 in wins, so the team performance shouldn't impact his output. However, with Sam Mitchell's eye on the future, they could do some experimenting, which we saw towards the end of 2022 when Sicily went from the preferred kick-out player (31%) to at times actively not looking to take the kick-ins, giving them up to the youngsters in Day and Bramble. He was even thrown into some centre bounces. Those things combined makes me think we'll see similar output again and be a top 6 defender. At that price though, I'd try to get him a bit cheaper during the season.
scShort: Averaged 118 in losses which is positive given Hawks will likely lose a lot and unless Mitchell goes full experimental mode, he could be around that mark again

scComment: Tom Mitchell has been a SuperCoach stud for the majority of his career, however that certainly wasn't the case in 2022. After finishing strong in 2021, averaging 129 in the second half of the season, we all thought the Tom Mitchell of old was back, after years of interruptions since breaking his leg in 2019. However, he missed the AAMI game with groin soreness which is never a good sign. That, combined with Sam Mitchell's desire to fast-track Hawthorn's rebuild and experiment with younger players through the midfield (53% CBAs compared to 70%+ in prior years) saw Tom Mitchell have his lowest SuperCoach average since his second season in the comp. He now finds himself at Collingwood, which is a massive win for his prospects, given they are contending and will certainly use Mitchell as a fulltime onballer. The only concern is the style Collingwood play (fast, low possession, move it forward) isn't conducive to high SuperCoach scoring. However, Mitchell can score in any environment if healthy and in the right role, so if he has an uninterrupted preseason, he becomes one of the early locks for me.
scShort: The move to a contender should see Mitchell return to being an elite SuperCoach player, making him an early lock at that price

scComment: Guthrie turned himself from a role player to low-key SuperCoach scorer over the past few years, averaging 103 since 2020. However, Geelong notoriously rest their players, particularly those over 30, and we saw that more than ever in 2022 with Guthrie playing a crazy low 69% game time. He rates 5th amongst midfielders on a points-per-minute basis, however I can't trust that the minutes and matches are always going to be there to do it.
scShort: Ranked 5th amongst midfielders on a points-per-minute basis in just 69% game-time, however I can't trust that the minutes and matches are always going to be there knowing what Geelong do with their 30-year-olds

scComment: It's hard to know what to make of Simpkin in SuperCoach. After a breakout season in 2020 which saw him increase his average by 22 points per game, he improved again in 2021 by another 4 points to 97 points per game and 105 post bye. However, he stagnated in 2022, reducing his average by 6 despite no Cunnington and increased CBAs minutes. A lot of that might have been due to how bad the Kangaroos were as scores are generally lower for losing teams and the Roos are that more often than not. The rise of LDU also took some ball off him, however long term this should be a good thing for Simpkins' prospects given LDU is now the Roos' best player and commands the oppositions' attention. I've seen enough from Simpkin to know that he can average 105-110 in a season, which would make him a nice selection at that price if it were to be this year. However, 110 still wouldn't be enough to challenge the top 8 mids in SuperCoach so you're better off spending a bit more for a Top 8 chance or less for someone who can generate more cash.
scShort: Was trending nicely before stagnating last year with the Roos' struggles, should improve his scoring this year but I doubt it will be by enough for him to challenge the top 8

scComment: Tim Taranto made quick impact in his SuperCoach career, averaging 104 in just his 3rd season. However, he's yet to reach those heights since. Aside from being prone to turning the ball over (5 clangers per game for the past 2 seasons), the competition for midfield minutes at the Giants has been the main factor holding him back, as he bottom out at 44% CBAs last season. He now finds himself at Richmond, who despite having a great team, aren't that deep in the midfield. Taranto should step into their preferred on-ball rotation and see his CBAs at 60%+ each week. CBAs bring SuperCoach gold, being a higher contested possession rate, more clearances and tackle opportunities. If this happens, we can swallow his 5 clangers a game much easier. If his preseason time trial is anything to go by, he's in for a big season and a 105 average is on the cards. And at his price, he'll prove a very worthwhile starting selection.
scShort: New club + forward status = 105+ on the cards

scComment: Another who needed a new club to bring career best form and he proved a gem for SuperCoachers who started with him in the forward line priced at 41. He averaged 100 from just 69% game time, so the upside would be an increased TOG from added fitness and Mundy retiring. However, he's now lost his forward status and nice price tag, and while he should continue in the inside role at Freo, I doubt he's going to improve on his price nor score enough to be a relevant starting selection this season in Fantasy.
scShort: Lost his forward status and nice price tag from last season meaning the 2022 hero shouldn't be in calculations this year

scComment: 2022 summed up Witherden's career to date, scoring great when he had the opportunity (7 scores over 100 from 12 games including a 152), but in and out of the side, playing just 12 games for a team who was easy to get games for. Its not a good sign and even if he scores well in the preseason, its hard to trust his job security for a player priced at 100.
scShort: Just 12 games for the struggling Eagles in 2022 so despite his scoring ability, its hard to trust his job security

scComment: If anyone has defied the 'players don't improve after 30' rule of mine, it's Trav Boak. He's been 105+ in his past 4 years which is crazy given he's now 34. He prepares as well and works as hard as anyone, so it doesn't come as a complete surprise. However, his scoring in the last 2 seasons suggest he's starting to slow down. His CBAs hit a low of 54% in this last 5 games, well down from his role of the past 5 years. With Butters and Rozee only increasing their midfield usage, I imagine Boak will reduce again. Could be relevant if given forward status during the season, but as a starting squad selection he's not a good option.
scShort: Likely to reduce again after a low of 54% CBAs in final 5 games as Butters and Rozee took over

scComment: Stewart averaged 120 for the first 11 rounds, including a 187 and 174, then it all went wrong. He was concussed in Round 12 just after quarter time when on 39 and on track to get 150 again. He returned with a low score, not uncommon for players returning from concussion and then bounced back with a 161, however got himself suspended for 4 weeks in doing so. He never returned the same player, averaging 91 in the last 5 and 85 in the finals, often receiving a heavy tag from opposition forwards. It's hard to predict Stewarts' prospects for 2023. On one hand, there's the fact he gets a lot of opposition attention (not ideal for a SuperCoach defender), he's now 30 in a team who notoriously rests their older players and that the Cats' style has evolved and they don't take as many marks. However, on the other hand you can get a player capable of a 120 average and being the number 1 defender priced at 110. I'm leaning to the second camp and believe he's a very decent D1 starting option at that price.
scShort: Rollercoaster 2022 saw him average 120 for the first 11 weeks, concussed, suspended then tagged to 91 in last 5 and 85 in finals makes it hard to read, but he's still one of the premium defenders in SuperCoach

scComment: Crisp became a full-time midfielder under McRae's first season, attending 58% CBAs and rotating forward rather than the half back role he had been accustomed to for the majority of his career. He was tested as a midfielder in the years prior and unconventionally scored lower when his CBAs were higher. This was the case in 2022, where Crisp went from a reliable 100 scoring defender to averaging 79 post bye and 76 in his last 5 games. While being incredibly frustrating for his Fantasy owners, he was still apparently doing his role for the team, winning Collingwoods best and fairest. He had a strong finals series, averaging 115 which was closer to what he scored in the first half of the season. If have a feeling he was carrying something in the second half of the season which explained the low scoring and low 100s is about where he should be in that midfield role. As a midfield only option though, that's nowhere near enough to consider as a starting option. He may come relevant if switched back to defence with Taylor Adams back and the arrival of Tom Mitchell, but given he won their B&F in the midfield role, it's hard to see that changing.
scShort: Incredibly frustrating for owners last year with 79 post-bye and while he should score closer to 100, the loss of defender status makes him not an option this time round, unless he picks up DPP during the season

scComment: Developed into a handy player with a nice Fantasy game. His season high of 130 was from 76% CBAs when Carlton were missing their first choice mids, but as a mid-only option, he's not going to get enough of those opportunities to be a successful Fantasy asset.
scShort: Developed into a handy player but not attractive as a mid-only option

scComment: Grundy has been on a steady decline - in real life and in SuperCoach - since 2019 when he was the number 1 player in the game. He now finds himself in a very unlikely scenario, playing alongside the best ruckman in the AFL, Max Gawn, after being pushed out of Collingwood. He's going to have a point to prove, it's just hard to see him getting enough opportunity in the middle to put up a score worthy of a top 2 ruck option. So despite his 30 point discount to his career best season, I'd need to see how the Dees use Gawn and Grundy before having either in my side.
scShort: Despite his 27 point discount to his career best season, I'd need to see how the Dees use Gawn and Grundy before having either in my side

scComment: Hurn is playing as well as ever, averaging a career high 105 in his 17th season, with his last 5 average ranking him as the seocnd best defender. However, the fact he's turning 36 this season, he's not a great option.
scShort: Coming off a career high but can't pick a soon-to-be 36 year old

scComment: Moore had a terrific 2022, firstly playing in his customary small forward role, where he managed to average 91 despite playing as a pure forward, and then when he was introduced into the midfield rotation and averaged 100 post bye from 42% CBAs. He was brilliant there and showed enough to suggest that role will continue into 2023. The chances are only enhanced following the departures of midfield regulars Mitchell and O'Merea. Looking at his consistency numbers, in his games less than 90 (8 of 22), he averaged 5% CBAs and over 120 (3 of 22) was 39% - a clear sign that in the midfield role, he's a solid scorer. With forward status, this is the type of player we're looking for in our starting sides, as long as those midfield minutes are there. His ownership will likely be low on name alone, but I like him as a discounted option with a chance to push the top 6.
scShort: The midfield move post bye netted 100 on 42% CBAs and is hopefully a sign of things to come which would put him in line to be a top 6 forward

scComment: O'Brien still hasn't reached the heights of 2020 that saw him emerge as one of the league's best ruckmen. Since then, he's regressed, which is rare for a ruckman of his age, to a point where he was dropped during last season. He dominated the SANFL with 35 possessions and 41 hitouts, showing he still has it, and returned to the senior team to average 105 for the rest of the season, including 6 scores over 120. However, there's enough evidence since Nicks took over as coach the Crows don't rely on O'Brien as much and certainly don't use him around the ground as they once did. He'll likely be a low-100 ruckman going forward so he'll be a handy Draft option, but there's not much value there in Classic.
scShort: He'll likely be a low-100 ruckman going forward so he'll be a handy Draft option, but there's not much value there in Classic

scComment: LDU broke out in 2022 in both real life and Fantasy. The former number 4 pick increased his average from 85 in 2021 to 101 in 2022, including 111 post bye, highlighted by an elite clearance game on 82% CBAs. After seeing how good he was around stoppages, it makes you wonder what Noble was thinking giving him just 59% CBAs pre bye. He's been a slow build since debuting, increasing his average by 23, 18, 4 and 16 points per game. His post-bye form suggest he's in for another 10+ point increase and may begin to knock on the door of the top 8 mids. The only thing that I see holding him back is the potential for opposition attention as he's now become the Roos' number 1 mid, surpassing Simpkin who has had to deal with the tag the last few seasons. If he avoids the tag enough and continues his post bye form (111), he'll prove a great starting selection priced at 101.
scShort: If the clearence stud avoids the tag enough and continues his post bye form (111), he'll prove a great starting selection priced at 101.

scComment: Duncan takes above average for marks (8.4 a game) and has a high kick to handball ratio of 2. Being a high mark player and playing at Geelong used to be a recipe for success, however they have changed their style so much in the last 12 months that there is less emphasis on a kick-mark game. Duncan finished the season playing in the backline and comes into 2023 with defender status, meaning hell be SuperCoach relevant throughout. The risk with Duncan is that he's now over 30 and had his share of soft tissue injuries in the past. We know Geelong aren't afraid to rest players, even if named. So you'll have nervous moments with him in 2023. For that reason, Id prefer to start with safer options in defence.
scShort: Capable of being a top 6 defender, but over 30 in Geelong always comes with risk

scComment: After teasing as a midfielder in 2020, Houston has been a mainstay in Port's defence. He's shown a high ceiling for a number of seasons now, scoring over 120 5 times in 2022 including a 144. However, he's also shown inconsistency, going sub-90 7 times. High ceilings are nice, but we need consistency in SuperCoach and over the full length of the season, I expect him to average around where he's been the past four years.

Lyons' regression from a top 8 SuperCoach mid in 2021 was one many saw coming. The Lions' midfield was criticised for be being a tad one paced, and they were forced to shake a few things up in 2022, with young guns McCluggage, Bailey and Rayner getting more midfield minutes. This saw Lyons reduce his CBAs from 80% in 2021 to 65% in 2022, including 53% in the last 5 games. It has come out that Lyons was dealing with OP in 2022 which may be a reason for the role and scoring drop off, however I feel like it was more to do with the need to inject youth and speed and the acquisition of Dunkley doesn't bode well for Lyons, who might find it hard remaining in the team, let alone the midfield rotation.
scShort: The acquisition of Dunkley doesn't bode well for Lyons, who might find it hard remaining in the team, let alone the midfield rotation

scComment: After averaging 110 in just his third season, the recruitment of Paddy Ryder to share ruck duties put a stop to Marshall's Fantasy trajectory. He's hovered in the low 100s since then, however showed his potential when given the solo duties. Marshall averaged 113 in the last 7 games Ryder missed to finish 2021 and 107 in the last 5 games of 2022 on 81% CBAs. With Ryder retiring and Ratten, the coach who preferred to use Marshall as a backup ruck, no longer there, we can expect Marshall to fulfill his SuperCoach and real life potential in 2023. With question marks over Gawn and Grundy playing together, Marshall will be a very popular starting ruck option - and for good reason. Update: Jack Hayes preseason injury might hurt as they are now missing Marshall and King for the early rounds, meaning Marshall could be needed up forward.
scShort: With Ryder and Ratten gone, expect Marshall to fulfill his SuperCoach and real life potential he showed when he averaged 110 in just this 3rd season

scComment: Lloyd was the premier defender in SuperCoach in 2019 and 2020. His scoring method was sustainable - the Swans' primary distributor, played on from every kick-in and consistently generating easy uncontested marks. This hasn't been the case in the past 2 seasons, dropping his average 15 points and then 16 points to 91 in 2022. The Swans had a clear change in game style, being more attacking from defence, meaning there were less easy plus six opportunities for Lloyd. He's also lost some kick-in duties to Nick Blakey after having a mortgage on them for years. He's still a consistent defender, it's just hard to see him ever reaching the 100+ heights of the past as the Swans continue to deploy their attacking game-style.
scShort: Hard to see him ever reaching the 100+ heights of the past as the Swans continue to deploy their attacking game-style

scComment: Whitfield has let down many coaches, including myself, the past 2 seasons. After back-to-back 105+ years, he's put up 94 and then 86 and looked a shadow of the hard-running, ball hungry, gun he was. Last year he was used on a wing and half forward, and rarely down back where he did most of his damage in the past. I think a change of coach could help reinvigorate him and get him back to his best, and I'm actually glad he's lost his defender status this year as it will save the tempation of starting with him.
scShort: Two down years in a row for the proven gun and if it weren't for his mid-only status, I'd be tempted to go back again

scComment: Cumming has backed up his impressive NEAFL numbers in 2019 and 2020 to become a handy defender for the Giants, both in real life and in Fantasy. A 95 average isn't enough to be a top 6 defender, but further improvement, which we've seen in every season he's been in the comp, could certainly push him there. His ball use is good enough to be a top 6, he just needs to see more of the ball. Cumming's worth a spot on the watchlist to see how the new coach and game style impacts his scoring.
scShort: Further improvement, which we've seen in every season he's been in the comp, could certainly push him towards the top 6 defenders

scComment: Witts had a terrific season, registering his career high SuperCoach average of 110. This was made even more impressive given he was fresh off an ACL injury and rewarded those who took the punt on his discounted price. He started the season crazy good, averaging 120 up until the bye to be one of the better players in SuperCoach. He was aided by his competition leading hit-out and hit-out to advantage numbers, which are gold for SuperCoach scoring. He regressed post bye, which was expected given his highest average pre-ACL was 100. He averaged 98 post bye and 102 in the final 5 games, which I think is a more accurate reflection of his capability. He should improve a bit with a full preseason under his belt, but priced at 110 and the second most expensive ruck option, I highly doubt he'll match those numbers again which rules him out as a starting squad selection for me.
scShort: Career high SuperCoach average of 110 fresh off an ACL was super impressive, but his post bye average of 98 is closer to where he's been thoughout his career and where I see him staying

scComment: Seb Ross had somewhat of a resurgence in 2022, increasing his average by 20 points per game. It was on the back of his move back into the midfield with 61% CBAs, up from 30% in 2021. A change of coach may reinvigorate Ross, but I highly doubt he'll begin to put up  any noteworthy SuperCoach numbers.
scShort: Back in the midfield rotation in 2022 but still yet to put up any noteworthy SuperCoach numbers

scComment: Vlastuin had a career best Fantasy year in his 10th season. He's always been on the radar in SuperCoach, given he's a former top 10 draft pick with thought of eventually moving to the midfield. However, he's become far too important of a defender to ever make the switch. With Houli retiring and Short moving into the midfield, Vlastuin became Richmond's primary distributor in defence, taking 36% of the kick-ins and averaging 100 points per game, up 18 on 2021. It could've been higher if not for an injury impacted 43, however injuries are something that have burdened Vlastuin for most of his career. He is an elite interceptor and a very good ball user, so he's always had the attributes to be a SuperCoach gun. He's still only 28 and will gain confidence from his career best year, so there's a chance he improves again in 2023. However, with the strengthening Tigers' midfield with Taranto and Hopper arriving, it's likely we'll see Short return to defence and take away some of Vlastuins usage. One to watch, but not in starting squad calculations for me.
scShort: Will have confidence coming off a career year but Short's likely return to defence and take away some of Vlastuins usage in 2023

scComment: Hall's SuperCoach career will go down as one of the biggest rollercoaster of emotions. He turned into an attacking half-back at the Roos where he was the number 3 forward in SuperCoach in 2021 and would've been number 1 if not for his 2 injury impacted games. However, his 2022 season began with a hamstring injury in the preseason and it didn't stop there. Hall had 2 games with less than 50% game-time (one with just 2 minutes) due to his ongoing hamstring and soft tissue injures. When not injured, he showed he still had it, with 3 scores over 120 in his 11 matches and a high of 153. However, he also (somehow) found himself out of the Roos' best 22 as they looked to play the youth. It's almost impossible to trust Hall in SuperCoach in 2022 given his hamstring woes, the fact he's now 32 and that he may not be in Clarko's 22 (at least, not in that attacking half back role which Xav tells me Clarko won't tolerate), so we're going to have to resist the temptation of a player capable of being the D1 priced at 98.
scShort: 32 with hamstring woes means we're going to have to resist the temptation of a player capable of being the D1 priced at 98

scComment: Dale has been a revolution since his move to defence, clearly putting up his best two SuperCoach seasons. He improved again in 2022, taking his average up 9 to 101. He shared the kick-in responsibilities (56%) which helped him score points and his solid ball use (82% efficiency) is a key feature of his game. He was averaging 106 in the first half of the season and was around the mark of the top 6 defenders, however slowed slightly as the season went on. He might produce a full season at 106, but I think you'd need more from someone at this price point as a starting squad selection.
scShort: Kick-in responsibilities (56%) and solid ball use (82% efficiency) are key features of his game, however 7 scores less than 90 make me doubt he can make it as a top 6 defender

scComment: Injuries have limited Prestia from fulfilling his Fantasy potential. After failing to play 10 games in the prior two seasons, Prestia played 19 in 2022, however in 3 of those he played less than 50% gametime due to early game injury. He's got the ability, however now on the other side of 30 and the fact Tigers have a deeper midfield, it's likely he will be managed a lot more in 2023 given his importance to their team structure. Add in the early game injury risk, he's certainly not someone I'm considering.
scShort: 3 games less than 50% game time after failing to reach 10 games in the two years prior makes the 30-year-old too much risk for me

scComment: Heeney has been the ultimate tease in SuperCoach and never as much as he was in 2022. After years of 'more midfield time' discussions in the preseason which never eventuated, it looked like it was finally going to happen after he had over 50% CBAs in the preseason practice match and Longmire backed it up with comments suggesting the move was real. However, he continued to play majority forward with small stints in the midfield - 18% in the first half of the season. They reduced as the year went on and his 4% CBAs post byes were not much more than he'd been getting in prior years. He still managed to score pretty well for almost a pure forward, averaging 101 points per game for the H&A season. This is why he's such a tantalizing prospect, if he can average 101 with 11% CBAs, imagine what he could do with 50%+! As a pure forward though, there's no value in his price as there was last year. So unless we see that 50% CBA number in the preseason and want to go down that road again, I'm not considering him as a strong starting option.
scShort: The ultimate tease has almost run out of 'more midfield time' chances, so unless we see 50%+ CBAs in the preseason, I won't be going down that road again

scComment: Now this kid can seriously play. After being introduced into the Swans' midfield rotation in 2021, Warner became a staple in 2022, attending 73% centre bounces in the second half of the year and 79% last 5. He's one of those players who are more damaging in real-life than in SuperCoach, showcased by his sub-100 average despite polling 12 Brownlow votes from the midfield. Heading into his 4th season and 3rd full year, he'll no doubt improve again with fitness and natural progression. A lot of this improvement might be counted by some additional opposition attention, such was the damaging nature of his game. So I think he'll bump his average up into the 100s for the first time in 2023, but he needs to be over 110 to be a worthwhile selection at that price which is hard to do for a 4th year player.
scShort: Heading into his 4th season, the future AFL star should improve again, but he'll no doubt receive extra attention which will make it tough to average the 110+ he needs to be a good selection

scComment: In a year where new club colours brought career best seasons (Hewett, Dawson etc), Cerra didn't get the memo. Arriving from Freo where he had four seasons of teasing us in Fantasy in sporatic scoring in various roles, he arrived at Carlton who at the time were crying out for midfield depth. This made me excited for the natural on-baller, who averaged 115 Fantasy points in NAB League, 10 more than now ex-teammate Andrew Brayshaw in the same team. However, while he did see career high CBA numbers (54%), he took a backseat to Cripps, Hewett and Walsh as the main three midfielders and averaged just 92 points. He was impacted by an early injury in one game and excluding that score of 5 he averaged 97. I think he can get that up to 105 in 2023, which could be lineball whether that is a worthwhile pick priced at 92. If he can get 110 then he's certainly worthwhile, but with his likely very low ownership, it's probably not worth the risk.
scShort: I expected more from 54% CBAs but 97 excluding lowest could bump to 105 in his second season at the Blues

scComment: After two flat seasons following his debut year, Rozee broke out in 2022. It wasn't all pretty though, but his progression and season splits certainly were. He averaged 51 in the first 4 rounds on 7% CBAs. He was then given consistent midfield opportunities and averaged 96 in his next 7 up until the bye from 56% CBAs. This role remained post bye, where he averaged 107. This is the sort of growth and splits we look for in Fantasy because we can get someone priced at their full season average (93) knowing they can average over 100 in the right role, plus any natural progression that we normally see when a player is just 4 seasons into their career. Rozee wasn't just a success in Fantasy, but starred in real life and went on to win Port's best and fairest award. That's enough for me to be confident in the midfield role remaining. And if anything, it could bump up to 70% with Boak phasing out. Midfield Rozee is a 100+ player which is enough to be a worthwhile pick priced at 92 and could be enough to be a top 6 forward for the season.
scShort: Averaged 103 following the midfield move and should only improve on that

scComment: Matt Crouch came into 2022 discounted after missing the entire 2021 season with groin issues. Some people have a hard rule of not picking players off an injury and they were proved right on this occasion. However, I like to look for a discount wherever I can and those same people would've missed out on someone like Sicily. There is no right answer, but one thing we have learnt is that it's very hard to trust someone with soft tissue injuries. Crouch, who was once a dominant midfielder of the comp both in real life and in SuperCoach, had his lowest season average since his second season of 90. He also struggled for regular games, playing just 11 for the season and 1 of the last 9. He clearly fell out of favour to the younger Sam Berry and Schoenberg. When he did play, he was restricted to just 67% TOG. I think the Crows have moved on from Crouch and it's likely he'll struggle for regular gametime again in 2023, so I'm ignoring that discount to his career best season and avoiding him in SuperCoach.
scShort: Former stud played 1 of the last 9 games and 67% TOG when playing, suggests the Crows have moved passed him

scComment: Serong has been a tease in Fantasy ever since he averaged 81 in his debut year. From there he hasn't really broken out, averaging 83 and 91 in his next two H&A seasons. The former top 10 pick ticks a lot of boxes and plays in a style that should see him be a SuperCoach stud in the future. It's no question midfielders rely on CBAs for scoring and while Serong has been a regular in there since his debut season (67%, 71% and 66%), he's yet to hit the 80%+ mark we see with the top SuperCoach mids. I didn't expect him to reduce his CBAs in 2022 following the departure of Cerra, however the emergence of Brodie (68%) and the evergreen Mundy (65%) weren't in my calculations. Mundy has retired which should open up a spot but it's likely that O'Meara will soak that up. It's becoming pretty crowded now at Freo, but I still think Serong will step up to 75%+ in his 4th season. That should give him enough opportunity to crack the 100 mark for the first time, which is better than what he's priced at, but not enough to challenge the top 8 mids in SuperCoach.
scShort: Waiting for the breakout since his debut and that could come this season if he can get his CBAs up to 75%

scComment: After dealing with hamstring and ankle injuries in his first two seasons, the former number 7 pick made himself at home in Freo's defence in 2023, playing 22 matches at an average of 92 points. His lethal kick was known, but it's his intercept work which has been just as impressive and both these attributes should bode well for his SuperCoach potential. He has all the makings of a star in real life, the question is when will he be a SuperCoach star. He showed he was capable of this during the finals where he averaged 113. It's the 12 scores under 90 that worry me and these will become less and less the more confidence he gains and the more he demands the ball. I feel like this is 6 months away so I'm resisting the temptation. However, if he displays this added hunger in the preseason or early rounds, I won't talk you out of it.
scShort: 98 in last 5 and 113 in finals suggests he can breakout in 2023 and push towards the 110 mark

scComment: The mid-season draft pick from 2021 came straight into the Hawks' side, finding his feet right away, setting the AFL record for tackles on debut with 14. However, his 2nd season was even more impressive. He went from what I thought has a hard working 'scrapper' to a genuine midfielder, finishing runner up in the Hawks' B&F behind defender James Sicily. If that wasn't a sign of him being their main man in the middle, then trading away veterans Mitchell and O'Meara is. At just 21 years old and another preseason under his belt, those CBAs should shoot to 75%+ and he could become a 100 averaging midfielder in 2023. However, it's hard to average 100 when your team is getting smashed most weeks, which is likely following the Hawks' offseason moves. That's enough to put a line through for me.
scShort: The runner-up B&F will be the main man without Titch and JOM, however it might be hard to score consistently in big losses

scComment: Daicos was as good as advertised. Playing down back, he was so clean and composed and finished the season with an average of 91. While it doesn't sound massive, his 91 average didn't do it justice as Collingwood's game style wasn't conducive to high scoring. In fact, he was the Pies' leading Fantasy scorer post their bye with 103. There are a few questions to ask for 2023. Does he remain in the backline or will he transition to the midfield? Will Collingwood play more of a high possession game style? Will opposition teams continue to lock down on him as we saw at times last season? There are enough unknowns for me to pass on Daicos as a starting squad option. However, the case has been there plenty of times before with second year players where if they look like taking a Taranto/Oliver sized leap, then you can jump on in the early rounds and do so with more confidence.
scShort: Collingwood's low scoring game style the main thing holding him back from being a top 6 option in his 2nd season

scComment: The damaging half back was a borderline top 6 defender from 2019-2020 when he had a mortgage on the Dogs' kick-in duties. However, since Dale has switched to defence in 2021, Daniel has dropped slightly and now finds himself outside the calculations for a top 6. Dale took 56% of the Dogs' kick-ins in 2022 compared to Daniel's 35%. An interesting point was that Daniel took 71% in the final and scored a 110. If he can ever return to the being main guy then he could be considered, but Dale looks pretty secure in that role for now.
scShort: Dropped to a level below the top 6 defenders ever since Dale moved to defence in 2021 and took the kick-in duties

scComment: Perryman has been a reliable wing/half back for the Giants since 2019, averaging 94 and 91 in 2020 and 2021. He was never in SuperCoach discussions given he was a step below the top 6 defenders, however his name popped up into lights when McVeigh took over as coach in Round 10 and gave Perryman his first CBAs. He attended 51% and scored a then season high of 138. A defender who played inside was certainly interesting, however it was short-lived after he injured his ribs 2 games later on 50 and missed the last 6 games. He did return to the midfield , highlighted by a 121 from 90% CBAs in Round 22. A defender priced at 95 who attended centre bounces and can score 130s is attractive, however McVeigh is gone and I doubt he'll be used in the middle for Kingsley, despite the loss of Hopper and Taranto. Predicting the Giants' CBA rotation has been an impossible task, so keep an eye on it in the preseason, but I think Perryman will return to a wing/half back role and be a mid-90s scorer. Regardless, he's lost his defender status for 2023 so he's not a strong option in Classic.
scShort: Lost his defender status after being used as a CBA mid under McVeigh and I think he'll return to a wing/HB role in 2023 which caps his output

scComment: It was apparent from early in his career that Butters was going to be a star of the comp one day. Unfortunately, it's meant a lot of coaches have backed him in for a breakout in Fantasy for two years now and been let down. However, he's had excuses. A bad ankle injury kept him to just 10 games in 2021, but that included a 163 in Round 2, and 96 before getting injured midway through the 3rd quarter in Round 4. Last season was a mix of big scores when given midfield time (4 scores over 120 when averaging 48% CBAs), low scores (5 under 70 from 33% CBAs) and injuries (MCL injury when on 68 before half time, the headknock with Jonas in the last qtr). However, when he had full fitness and played in the right role, he showed he can be a top 6 forward after all, averaging 116 in his last 5 games. The forward line is getting crowded with a number of great starting options and Butters takes on more risk - role and injury due to his bash-and-crash nature - than the others. However, I'm a believer and think he can be a 110+ averaging forward this season, which would make him a great pick at this price.
scShort: We've waited 2 years for the Fantasy breakout and his 116 in the last 5 of 2022 could be a sign of things to come

scComment: Ellis has the Fantasy game that is capable of putting up some monster scores. He had 4 scores over 120 last year, following his 6 over 110 in 2021. He's gained defender status for 2023, which keeps him in the discussion as there aren't many defenders with that scoring ability. His kick-in rate increased as the season went on which lead to higher scoring. However, as the Suns become more competitive, there are less slow plays where Ellis is the beneficiary of some easy plus 6ers. He'll likely have some high scoring games again in 2023, but mixed with some low scores (11 games sub-90 in 2022). He'll be a level below the top 6 in Fantasy.
scShort: High ceiling and defender status makes him relevant in 2023, but I've got him just below the top 6 given his inconsistency

scComment: After finishing 2021 as a top 2 ruck and one of the best scorers in SuperCoach, Darcy had a disappointing 2022. It started in the preseason where nothing went right. He broke a thumb, had sore groins and then an Achilles injury that kept him out of the first practice match and Round 1. It's the second interrupted preseason in a row for Darcy after his knee injury in 2021 and it showed, struggling in his AAMI game and being named emergency in Round 1. He looked more of his 2021 self post bye, but still lacked the scoring power of 2021. His season high of 178 came from 89% CBAs, and this is the CBA level we'd love him to be consistently. He's been a 68%-73% CBA ruckman the last two years, largely due to the interrupted preseasons. The hope of that reaching 80%+ took a hit in the preseason with the recruitment of Luke Jackson, who you'd think will ruck more than Rory Lobb did last season. Lobb averaged 20%, which isn't a heap, it was more Meek who took over 60% when playing. Meek is gone so the outlook for Darcy might not be as grim as some are predicting. I think he'll ruck 70% which is more than what he did in 2021, so don't rule him out of being a top 2 ruck heading into his peak-ruck period of season 7.
scShort: Ready to breakout after 2 interrupted preseasons in a row, however the arrival of Jackson will put a cap on that

scComment: Is there a 28 gamer that has had more airtime in SuperCoach than Braydon Preuss? After missing his full first season at the Giants, many were relying on Preuss to be their R2 in 2023. On face value, he was a success when he played, averaging 100 points per full game played. While he did make a lot of cash for owners, tIt was the fact he only played 10 games and got injured/suspended/dropped at the wrong time all year. Sadly, this has been the consistent story for Preuss his entire career. There's no doubt he's a very good SuperCoach scorer when on the park, but he's become too hard to trust. When he was priced in the 60s as he has been for his entire career, then it was a risk worth taking. But now that he's priced at 92, I'd rather start with a ruck with equal upside and less downside (i.e. English and Marshall).
scShort: 2nd amongst rucks for PPM in 2022, unfortunately it's the M that we can't trust him playing every week

scComment: Nank has been a consistent ruck since arriving at the Tigers, averaging between 89 and 98 in 5 of the past 6 seasons. That's nice to rely on in Draft, but he's never going to be the top 2 ruck we're hunting for in Classic.
scShort: Between 89 and 98 in 5 of the past 6 season so hard to see that changing

scComment: The former mature aged draftee has been a consistent SuperCoach defender since debuting, however outside of his B&F and AA 2020 season, has always been a level below the top 6 defenders. An elite user of the ball (88% disposal efficiency) with a high kick-to-handball ratio and a nice marking game, he has the attributes to go big and does so every so often, highlighted by a 156 last season. However, I feel hell give up a few extra touches to Hayden Young this year and likely remain that level below the top 6.
scShort: A consistent defender since debuting, however might be capped as Hayden Young becomes more prominent

scComment: A much-improved season in real life and in Fantasy and now finds himself at the Blues where he should have a wing to himself. Wingmen don't score premium-mid SuperCoach numbers, so while he could match his career high, he's not going to be in the conversation.
scShort: Wingmen are capped to the 90 mark in SuperCoach so this is the best he'll be

scComment: At his best, the West Coast captain can easily eclipse his price, being 20 points less than his 2019 season. Unfortunately, he's struggled with soft tissue injuries since then, playing just 37 games in 3 years at less than 70% game time. His PPM is still good enough, but you can't trust the 32 year old in your Classic team.
scShort: 37 games in 3 years at less than 70% game is too risky for a 32-year-old

scComment: Redman had a career best season in real life and in SuperCoach, bumping his average up from 76 to 93. However, it was highlighted by his 3 120+ scores including a 176. What caught the eye was his 127 average in wins. Unfortunately, the Bombers didn't win many games and his average was impacted by his 78 in losses. With the Bombers likely to improve in 2023 and Redman still just 25, we can expect him to increase his average again which would see him knocking on the door of the top 6 defenders. His inconsistency makes him a risk (6 sub-70 scores), but he'll be a super unique option for anyone willing to take a punt.
scShort: Averaged 127 in wins in 2022 which catches the eye given Essendon should be winning a lot more this season

scComment: Smith has been a consistent 80-90 player for the majority of his career. His forward status gives him some relevance in Draft but with the amount of quality options up forward, the 34-year-old isn't a consideration in Classic.
scShort: 80-90 isn't bad for a forward but not with the other quality ones out there

scComment: After 13 seasons in a row averaging at least 100, Pendlebury put up his 2nd 90s average in a row to show that he is finally slowing down. He was still asked to play a prominent role in the Pies' midfield, attending 61% of their centre bounces. This is more of a sign of the lack of depth in the Pies' midfield last season. However, with the arrival of Tom Mitchell and hopefully a healthy Taylor Adams, I expect we might see Pendles taking a step back in 2023. This could mean he gets DPP at some stage during the season, but I think we won't see an increase in scoring from the 35-year-old.
scShort: Likely to take a step back which might mean DPP at some stage but unlikely to increase his scoring

scComment: Green has steadily improved in each of his 3 seasons, however the Giants' midfield logjam has stopped him from really breaking out. Arriving into the league as a highly-touted, Cripps/Oliver type, he clearly needed some time to get his fitness up to AFL standard, playing just 66% and 71% in his first 2 seasons. However, his contested rate and efficiency has always been in line with the top SuperCoach midfielders, he just needed more opportunity to win the ball. He looked like a man last season and his 82% TOG was a great sign. However, his 58% CBAs was not. He had his chances early in the season and looked good, but reduced his midfield time as the year went on. With Hopper and Taranto gone, Green is the obvious beneficiary and should see his CBAs jump to over 70% in 2023. That should be enough for him to gain an extra 4 touches per game and than really be in line with the top 8.
scShort: The obvious beneficiary of Hopper and Taranto leaving and if he gains an extra 4 touches per game while maintaining his elite contest and efficiency rate, he could well be a top 10 mid

scComment: After a career best Fantasy year in 2021 in his 13th season, Rich returned to the 90s guy he's been for the majority of his career. That's not enough to consider the 32-year-old.
scShort: 32 and back to scoring in the mid-90s

scComment: After a shocking 2021 where he lost his place in Essendons first-choice midfield mix, Shiel bounced back somewhat to average 92. After the bye he returned to be a high CBA player and averaged 110. He's never been a 110 scoring midfielder and while if he can maintain this role then under Scott he may be under priced, I'd be very surprised if he has a career best SuperCoach season at age 30.
scShort: Hard to see him repeating the 110 post bye from 76% CBAs

scComment: Sam Berry was given every chance to succeed in 2022, playing prime midfield minutes over the likes of leadership group member Ben Keays and former B&F winner Matt Crouch. This shows Adelaide must rate him highly, and he showed a great amount of improvement. He led the comp in tackles per game, which is a great achievement for a 21-year-old in his first full season in the midfield. Normally the leading tacklers are SuperCoach studs, however his 17.6 disposals per game are a long way off what they need to be to be a relevant SuperCoach midfielder. His contested rate is also above that of SuperCoach elite mids and with another preseason he should improve again, but I doubt it's by enough to make him a decent pick in SuperCoach.
scShort: Crows love him with 76% CBAs post bye and led comp in tackles per game, just needs to win more of it to be relevant as a mid-only

scComment: The sky looked the limit after his 92 and 104 in his first two seasons in the comp. However, hes put up back-to-back 80s since moving to West Coast.
