I was pretty bullish on him last season following reports he was back in career best condition, however early season Covid and then the West Coast struggles meant he had another disappointing season. At 28, he should be at his peak, meaning averaging 104 again isn't out of the question. However, he'd need to be a keeper to be a worthwhile selection at that price in SuperCoach, and I doubt he will suddenly put up 110.
scShort: Due for a bounceback after back-to-back mid-80s, but needs to hit 110 to be a worthy selection which I doubt he can do

scComment: Looking back on my comments of past season guides, I've always had hope that Gresham will breakout. He'd teased us when given CBAs, averaging 90 after Round 10 in 2019 when introduced into the midfield, but then returned to a small forward role the following year. The Saints' midfield is very one paced and I thought someone crafty like Gresham should be used more in there. We saw that consistent midfield role come to fruition in 2022, however he underperformed from a scoring point of view, averaging 88 points from 60% CBAs. His disposal efficiency, effective rate, clangers and tackles were all below the top 6 forwards, which isn't a good sign for his future SuperCoach prospects. It's unknown where he will play under Ross, but I've now seen enough to know that he's a better player in real life than in SuperCoach and I doubt he'll trouble the top 6 forwards.
scShort: Finally saw consistent CBAs (60%) but scoring was a bit off the top 6 and future role under new coach is unknown

scComment: Outside of his 2020 season where he was used in the midfield in the absence of Shuey and Yeo, Duggan had a career high SuperCoach season, averaging 83 points per game. His 101 in the his last 5 games caught the eye, however, a lot of it was with how West Coast faired last season and they played a lot of slow football down back to control the scoreboard. I doubt they will play the same way in 2023 and while he should be in his peak at 26, mid-80s appear about him, which won't be enough to see him be a top 6 defender.
scShort: Should be in his peak and mid-80s appear about that, which won't be enough to see him be a top 6 defender

scComment: Heppell averaged 99 in his first season in defence in 2021 but dropped to 87 which was surprising as I thought he would improve in his second season in the role with more confidence. However, the Bombers are full of distributors down back, with Redman, Ridley, Hind and D'Ambrosio all very good kicks of the football and Heppell, a career 63% kicking efficiency, took a back seat. I doubt he'll gain more usage down there, especially with McGrath touted to return to defence. So despite his discount to his best, I think he'll be an 80s guy going forward.
scShort: Dropped his average in his second season in defence as he took a back seat to the plethora of Bomber distributors and hard to see that changing in 2023

scComment: Jed caught the eye in 2020 when he had one of the best points-per-minute in the comp (minimum two games) on his way to a 104. This included 4 scores over 140, including a 174. He never reached those heights again and the Roos moved on from him at the end of 2022. Now at the Suns, he is there as a depth midfielder who I still rate highly, but I doubt he'll ever get the midfield opportunities he had when he was a SuperCoach relevant player (62%).

Cameron returned to the 90+ Fantasy forward in 2022 after back-to-back 70s. Key forwards a very rarely relevant in SuperCoach, however Cameron does score more than the average key forward. However, in a year with so many midfield options in the forward line, there is no chance of Cameron competing with the top tier.
scShort: Scores better than the average key forward, but that's not enough in a year full of fwd/mids

scComment: Gulden is part of the young Swans brigade who all look like they are going to be stars of the comp. Playing predominantly as a high half forward, Gulden moved to a wing in the second half of 2022 and looked great, however his scoring took a dip from 88 in the first half to 83 in the second. Wingmen typically don't score great in SuperCoach given their very low percentage of disposals being contested. In fact, he scored more Fantasy points in the second half compared to the first, it just didn't suit the SuperCoach scoring methodology. Players typically take a big step in their 3rd season and I think we'll be seeing Gulden take over a few games in 2023. The question is can he become a keeper which he will need to be at that price to be a worthwhile selection? The fact he's likely to be a wing and not attend many centre bounces (10% in 2022) makes it hard. And in a year where there are plenty of forward options who have great CBAs, I think it's best to play it safe and go with the proven guys.
scShort: Will be a top 6 one day, I just don't think it's this season while he's still on the wing

scComment: Tuohy a found a nice role in defence for the Cats and been a decent scorer for the majority of his career now. Amazingly, he produced a career high average in 2022, despite being 33. However, the fact his career best season (90) was ranked 29th amongsts defenders means he's not an option in SuperCoach.
scShort: The 33 yr old had a career best season SuperCoach season, but still ranked him as the 29th defender

scComment: After ankle surgery in the preseason, Zorko had his worst return of his career in 2022, struggling with injury and form to average 82 points for the season. Remarkably, he had 3 games with less than 50% game time. Removing those and his average wasn't that bad. Zorko has been a SuperCoach stalwart throughout his career. His scoring is boosted by above average kick-to-handball ratio at a great efficiency. Combined, he's a unique player who doesn't require 30 touches to get a decent SuperCoach score. And when he does get 30 touches, he can push out some monster scores. With the buzz around young guns Dunkley, Taranto and Rozee, Zorko could be the bargain buy of them all. However, it would take a brave coach. He's now 34 and coming off the year of niggles. It's the sort of risk I don't normally take with my SuperCoach team, especially given the number of good forwards available. But if you're willing to take the risk, then it could certainly pay off.
scShort: 3 games less than 50% in 2023 means he could be a bargin buy, but not for the faint hearted

scComment: O'Meara has arrived at a far more Fantasy friendly environment and looks set to take a prominent role in their midfield. Mundy has retired and surprisingly took up 65% CBAs on very low TOG. Serong's 66% will get a boost, but beside him I think we will see something similar from Brayshaw and Brodie. That means O'Meara could carve out 65%+ CBAs, which is only a touch more than what he averaged last year, but in a better environment. O'Meara has had an underwhelming Fantasy career, impacted by injuries throughout. The fact that a man of his talent hasn't averaged 100 in a season in his 11 seasons is a shock. So while I see him bouncing back this year, it's hard to see him becoming a keeper which you'd need him to become at that price.
scShort: Yet to average 100 in his 11 seasons, so despite the improved environment, it's hard to see him being a top 8

scComment: Rowbottom has always been highly rated at the Swans, however appeared to be overtaken by some of the new draftees in 2021, reducing his CBA numbers from the year prior and even finding himself out of the side. However, returned to be one of their 4 key mids in 2022 with 50% CBAs alongside Parker (72%), Warner (63%) and Mills (56%). The way he finished the season (86 post bye and 109 last 5) indicated that he'll be a prime onballer of the future. With Parker now into his 30s, it's likely to be a Mills, Warner and Rowbottom midfield for years to come. I think we'll see his CBAs bump up to above 60% in 2023. He tackles as well as any of them (6.8 per game compared to 6.0 from the top 8 mids) and his contested rate (49%) is also inline with the top 8 mids. However, he lacks the outside game which will restrict his scoring for now and averages just 18 touches per game, which is about 10 less than the elite mids in the comp. At his price, you'll need him to be a borderline keeper (top 10-12 mid) for it to be a worthwhile selection. This will come, but I think it's 12 months away, so I'm not as bullish on him as others seem to be.
scShort: Needs to bump his disposal count from 18 per game to go with his top 8 level tackle and contest rate to regularly put up the 109 he did in the last 5 games of 2022

scComment: Saad had an outstanding season and finished at an All Australian half back, indicating he's one of the top few defenders in the league. This was reflected in his SuperCoach scoring, averaging a career high 103 which puts him just behind the top 6 defenders for 2023. Saad is so damaging with ball in hand that he now is the preferred shut down target for opposition sides. He obviously has the game to be a top 6 defender, highlighted by his 112 in the last 5 games, I just don't like trusting the low possession / high impact players (averages just 22 touches per game compared to 25 of top 6).
scShort: Ranked 7th amongst defenders and his last 5 would put him clearly in the top 6, I just find it hard to trust low possession / high impact players in my SC team

scComment: After being a big scorer at reserve level as number one ruck, Cameron finally had the chance to showcase his ability at AFL level after Grundy went down in Round 6. He averaged 97 in the 16 games since and showed enough that the Pies traded Grundy at season end, meaning he'll be their main man next year. Given he averaged 47 in the first 5 games (one as the sub), he comes into 2023 priced at 86, 11 points less than what he showed he can do as first ruck. With English and Marshall set to eclipse that, many are overlooking Cameron for 2023. However, he only attended 55% of the centre bounce ruck contests in 2022, given the Pies' preference to use him forward and play Cox in the ruck a bit. The offseason recruitment of McStay will likely see Cox pushed out of the side and McStay playing as second ruck, and there is no way he will be doing 45%. Therefore, Cameron could increase his usage to 70%+, meaning a bump in average could be on the cards. If this bumps to 105, which it could with 70% CBAs, then he could prove a very nice point of difference in the ruck department or an underpriced forward.
scShort: Averaged 97 after Grundy went down and McStay in could mean even more CBAs than his 55% last season

scComment: Became a regular for the Hawks in 2022 on a wing, playing 21 games. Wingmen aren't great in SuperCoach, particularly when they are mid-only. Not relevant in SuperCoach.
scShort: Wingman who is mid-only, not a SuperCoach option

scComment: After 11 games in 2 seasons following an impressive debut season, Clark returned to form in his first year at Freo. He averaged 88 from a half back flank and pushed that to 93 post bye. I think if it weren't for Luke Ryan and Hayden Young, then he would have the potential to push his average into the 100s and be a SuperCoach relevant defender. However, for a decent kick, he takes very little kick-ins (3%) and is not the primary distributor. Therefore, I doubt he'll push to that level and more likely remain as a mid-to-high-80s defender.
scShort: Behind Young and Ryan for distributor duties meaning he'll likely remain at his mid-to-high-80s average

scComment: Adams has now had two injury impacted seasons in a row. The man who has averaged 110 twice in his career battled with hamstring and knee issues early 2022 which kept him to 76 in the first half of the season. He looked back to full fitness and went at 105 post bye. I thought he was underpriced in 2022, however it was a groin issue that restricted him all year, playing a career low 73% game time, and finally gave way with a complete rupture of his adductor in the final. He's recovered well and should be right to get enough preseason in before Round 1. Therefore, he becomes a discounted option for 2023 being priced at 80. The concern is that he could be managed, which we saw in parts of 2022 where he played sub-70% game time on a lot of occasions. It will be made easier now that Tom Mitchell will take the prime inside mid role. There is also risk of reinjury, which looking at 3 of his past 4 seasons you'd have to say he's now an injury prone player. The Pies also play a less possession heavy game style now than they did when Adams was going 110. However, if you're a high risk / high reward coach, then Adams could a nice unique. He is more of a Fantasy player than SuperCoach given his very high clanger rate (5 per game, 1st amongst mids in 2021).
scShort: Has averaged 110 twice and is priced at 80, but recent injury history the concern

scComment: I've been a bit anti-Gaff for a few seasons and a reason why I don't like wingmen/outside mids in SuperCoach. When West Coast were strong, he was super consistent using hard running to gather uncontested possessions and Fantasy points at will, with multiple seasons over 105. But he lacked the inside strength and tackling game to generate consistent 'uber-premium' 110+ scores, even when things were good. And then when the team is less competitive and the possessions drop off like they have the past two seasons, he's prone to sub-par scores (10/16 games under 90, something you'd never see a few years back). While I suspect he'll bounce back a bit in 2023, it's not going to be by enough to be worth starting with.
scShort: Two down seasons in a row comes with being an outside mid in a poor side and while both WC and Gaff should be better in 2023, it won't be by enough to be worthwhile

scComment: After a prolific junior career and earning his stripes in defence once drafted, McGrath shifted to the midfield in 2020. He looked good initially and I thought on track to be a SuperCoach stud, but his midfield time reduced and hes been in no mans land for the past 4 years, playing wing, on ball and half back. Brad Scott has come out and said he wants to settle McGrath off a half back flank, and while I feel like he could still make it as an inside mid, a settled position should be good for his development. At age 24, he should be entering his peak. However, with competition for distribution at the Dons, with Redman, Ridley, Hind and D'Ambrosio taking a lot of kicks, I dont think well see McGrath breakout to be a top 6 defender this season.
scShort: A move to defense for the former number 1 pick should see some improvement but he'll need a lot of improvement to challenge the top 6 defenders

scComment: Swallow is an honest competitor and been a consistent scorer in the 80-90 range for most of his career. However, a career best year of 103 in 12 seasons and fresh off a 86 isn't enough to consider as a midfield option in SuperCoach. Keep an eye on him for Draft as he's one who may gain DPP over the year, but even then he'll unlikely feature.
scShort: A long way off the top ones as a mid-only, best chance will be if he gains DPP during the season and comes into Fantasy relevance

scComment: The 32-year-old has played every game in the last 2 years and got decent CBA opportunity, which was interesting considering some of his younger teammates struggled for time in the middle. He's been a tough player for the Giants but I doubt he'll see as much midfield time under the new coach. I expect we've seen the best of Ward and he's not a relevant Fantasy option.
scShort: Might struggle for midfield opportunity this season and won't have SuperCoach relevance

scComment: There was a bit of buzz around Lipinski this time last year after his trade to the Pies. He showed great signs from limited opportunities at the Dogs and put up some monster scores at VFL level. He led the Pies for CBAs in the preseason game and if it weren't for an early ankle injury in the AAMI, he would've started in a lot more sides. Those who jumped off were kicking themselves after Round 1 as Lipinski scored 133 from 48% CBAs and was everywhere. However, he only hit 48% CBAs twice more for the season and dropped to 19% in his last 5. His scoring never took off, averaging 86 for the season with reducing splits as the season went on. He heads into 2023 with forward status, however with the arrival of Tom Mitchell and fitness of Taylor Adams, I doubt we'll see him get the midfield opportunities he needs to compete with the top 6 forwards.
scShort: Forwards status is nice but doubt he'll get the midfield opportunities he needs to be a top 6

scComment: Himmelberg's switch to defence midseason was a masterstroke by stand-in coach, McVeigh. It was one I never saw coming and he averaged 98 as a defender, after averaging 63 as a key forward. He didn't just score well, but he made an impact and looked at home in defence, not playing as a key defender but as one of their prime movers back there. If he were to continue in that role in 2023 then he's an obvious underpriced option, priced at 91 when we've seen him score 110 in the role. However, new coach Kingsley comes from Richmond and I highly doubt he will let the Giants play the slow kick-mark game they showcased last year. Also, word is that he's back training with the forwards, which makes sense given their number of tall defenders and lack of tall forwards. Therefore, I'm not sure you can do it, despite that attractive discount to his post bye average.
scShort: Averaged 110 as a defender but word is he's training with the forwards which puts a dampener on what looked like an underpriced option

scComment: Naitanui's point per minute impact in SuperCoach has always been elite. Even last year which was a down season for him where he copped a lot of criticism, he still managed to have the highest PPM amongst ruckmen. Unfortunatly, he plays so little game time  never touching 70% in 5 seasons. It was fine in 2021 when he went at 168 points per 100% game time. However, he had his lowest PPM in the previous 5 years last season and for the first time ever seemed to have lost his spring and impact. Sadly, I think hes past his peak and we wont see him average much more than he did in 2022.
scShort: PPM gun but even that was down last season and safly I think we've seen the best of him

scComment: I don't think anyone saw Nic Martin's debut season coming. The mature aged recruit who trained with West Coast in the preseason before signing with Essendon, averaged 76 Fantasy points in the WAFL the year prior and came out and averaged 79 at AFL level, including a 114 on debut. He still looked very raw despite being mature aged and the with amount he improved with less than 1 preseason, I think he'll greatly benefit from a full preseason. However, as an outside wingman, I doubt he could improve enough to be Fantasy relevant this season. He retained his forward status which is handy but at his price he will need to be around the top 6 forwards to be a worthwhile selection, and I doubt that's going to happen.
scShort: Great debut season and should improve again but scoring is capped as an outside wingman so I doubt he'll challenge the top 6

scComment: After averaging 84 in his second season, Burton looked to be a star Fantasy defender of the future. He hasn't matched that average since in 5 seasons. Unfortunately, he hasn't come on and you can't take the risk on him turning it around this year.
scShort: Hasn't come on as I though he was going to after his 84 average in year 2

scComment: Cotchin plays a perfect team game for the Tigers and as a result, hasn't been a factor in SuperCoach for a number of years now. Certainly not an option this year, especially considering hell likely lose midfield time to Hopper and Taranto.
scShort: Hasn't had a SuperCoach game for 5 years now

scComment: De Goey burst into SuperCoach relevance in 2021 when he was shifted into the midfield and averaged 110 for the second half of the season. McRae kept him in there for the full season, attending 77% of the CBAs, however never met those scoring heights, averaging 85 for the regular season. It was a mixture of both McRae's low possession game style and the focus for De Goey to get his possessions in a dangerous position forward of centre. We might see him spend a bit more time forward as the Pies' midfield depth should be deeper with Tom Mitchell and hopefully Adams rotating in there, so I doubt we'll see the 100+ De Goey again under McRae. As a mid-only option, he's certainly not one to consider starting with.
scShort: First full season as a midfeilder however McRae's lower possession game plan and focus to get the ball forward of centre means he might not be that 100+ player again

scComment: Aish has become a reliable role player for Freo, playing a range of positions which included being a tagger in 2022 but mainly as a wingman. He's a mid 70s type player, which certainly doesn't make him relevant in SuperCoach, particularly as a mid-only.
scShort: Versatile role player not one for SuperCoach

scComment: Once a relevant SuperCoach forward fell out of favour last season, playing just the 7 games at an average of 68. Now 31, it's likely he'll struggle for games again, especially considering Geelong's off season recruiting.
scShort: Will likely struggle for games again

scComment: Moved into the midfield with great team impact in 2022, highlighted by his strong tackle pressure. He had a small bump in output (80 pre bye on 15% CBAs to 88 post when CBAs went to 59%) but 88 is still not enough to be a relevant defender. Should improve again with Selwood out, but I think he's one of those who is too team orientated to make a impact in SuperCoach.
scShort: Pressure midfielder who is too team orientated to make an impact in SuperCoach

scComment: Rioli was a revelation in 2022, switching to half back and becoming a star running defender of the comp. The move improved his Fantasy output by 30 points per game to finish with 92 for the season. There's no question he'll remain in the role, even if Short moves back again, but he'll unlikely push that average to the mark needed to be a relevant defender this season.
scShort: Starred down back and will remain in that role but unlikely push that average to the mark needed to be a relevant defender

scComment: Byrne-Jones has been a 70s/80s guy for the past 5 seasons. That's about him I think, so he's not worth considering in Fantasy.
scShort: A 70s/80s defender

scComment: The Big O has become a solid ruck, averaging 88 for the past 3 seasons. While solid, he's had the number 1 mantle at the Lions for long enough to know that he's never going to challenge the top few in SuperCoach.
scShort: Averaged 88 since being the number 1 ruck

scComment: The former number three pick looked set to fulfill his potential in 2019, pushing up the ground to average 99 points per game, including 106 in the last half. Unfortunately, he hasn't gone on with it, dropping his average in every season since to finish on 75 last year. At 27, he should be in his prime and may appear underpriced to what he could produce. However, Billings needs two things to be relevant in Fantasy; forward status and CBAs. Unfortunately, he's available mid-only and attended no centre bounces last season.
scShort: Reduced his averaged every year since 2019

scComment: Daicos has been used predominantly as a wingman, which isn't a great role for SuperCoach scoring with the lack of contested possessions on the outside. He saw some CBAs in the back half of 2022, averaging 22% post bye, and naturally improved his average to 89 from 71. The Pies were light on for inside mids, but with Tom Mitchell's arrival and a healthy Taylor Adams, I expect Daicos to move back to his wing role, which means he'll be capped with his scoring output in 2023.
scShort: Scoring is limited when on the wing which is where he'll likely play in 2023

scComment: Smith has been a consistent defender for a number of years now without taking that next step and being a Fantasy relevent one. His kick-ins are low for someone with such a nice kick (only 31%) as he's made way for Dawson to be the main man back there. While Dawson is playing in defence, I doubt we'll see Smith pushing that average much higher.
scShort: While Dawson is playing in defence, I doubt we'll see Smith pushing that average much higher

scComment: Coleman was a popular mid-priced starting option in 2022 after scoring 87, 90 and 77 in his last 3 games of 2021 following a move to defence. However, it was short lived as Coleman had a delayed start due to a preseason hamstring injury, but returned to produce a breakout season, averaging 87 and looking great as a defender. He showed enough to suggest he could one day be a top 6 SuperCoach defender, averaging 97 post bye as his kick-in numbers increased and he gained more confidence. However, I just doubt that he can produce top 6 numbers while Rich is still around taking the majority of the kick-ins.
scShort: Breakout 2022 with 97 post bye but unlikley to be a top 6 while Rich is still around

scComment: The former top 10 pick has had a mixed Fantasy career. After a career high season in 2020 which included a 10 week stretch averaging 118, he moved to a wing in 2021 and Hall and Ziebell took his role as the easy accumulator. McDonald's average dropped to just 68 points in this wing role. He returned to defence last season and improved his average, but was far from the role that saw him be a top defender in 2020. It's unclear what role he'll play under Clarko, but I think one things is for sure that they won't be doing the slow 'chip-mark' game that the Roos have played for the last 3 seasons. One to watch, but you'd need certainty on role before selecting him.
scShort: Has it in him to go big as we saw in the back end of 2020, just don't know what role Clarko will have for him

scComment: Newman has had flashes of SuperCoach brilliance throughout his career, however he's never put together a full season. Hes behind Docherty and Saad for distribution duties, which means hes too inconsistent to rely on in SuperCoach.
scShort: Too inconsistent to rely on in SuperCoach

scComment: Dunstan has shown he's a genuine Fantasy scorer when given the opportunity, however it's the opportunity that he has struggled with his whole career. He played 4 games in his first season at the Dees and will likely remain a depth player behind their star mids.
scShort: Will likely remain a depth player behind the Dee star mids

scComment: Hind backed up his breakout 2021 with a 89 average in 2022. He's a good player and I'd be surprised if his role changes much under the new coach. However, there is no shortage of distributors in defence at the Dons so I doubt we'll suddenly see an increase in average anytime soon.
scShort: No shortage of distributors in defence at the Dons so I doubt we'll suddenly see an increase in average anytime soon

scComment: Walker's late-career resurgence has been great to watch. However, outside of averaging 118 after 6 rounds in 2021, he's still a key forward and key forwards aren't what you want in SuperCoach.
scShort: Scores above average for a key forward however key forwards aren't what you want in SuperCoach

scComment: Parfitt hasn't been a factor in SuperCoach even when he had forward status. He's now only available in the midfield, and considering he was in and out of the side at the end of 2022, he's not worth considering in Fantasy.
scShort: Mid-only and behind in the pecking order now at Geelong

scComment: Fox had a career best average of 75 in 2021, but remained on the fringe in a strong Swans team. I think it will be much the same in 2023.
scShort: Never played more than 15 games in a season and always seems to be on the fringe

scComment: SPP had a career best season, playing all 22 games as a strong bodied forward. After bursting onto the scene 6 years ago, I had him earmarked to be a midfielder for years to come. However, he's found it hard for midfield minutes and bottomed out last season at just 3%. He's clearly not in calculations anymore and been surpassed by Rozee and Butters, so I think that forward role will be him going forward. In that role, it's hard to see him ever averaging much more than 75.
scShort: Settled in a forward role last season which produced a career best season but not good enough for SuperCoach

scComment: The ever-green 34-year-old full forward is playing as well as ever in real life and continues to put up to 10 forward numbers in SuperCoach. However, he crosses two of my boxes in age and role, so I'd much rather own a young player with midfield potential in my SuperCoach forward line.
scShort: Ever-green but hard to see him maintaining his top 6 numbers

scComment: Curnow's return in 2022 was overshadowed by the other remarkable comebacks of Docherty, Sicily and Witts, but he managed to put up career best numbers and win the Coleman after returning from 4 games in 2 years. Prior to his knee issues, he was looking like he may transition to a tall wingman role in the Kouta-mould, a far more SuperCoach friendly role. However, given how dominant he was playing as a key forward last year, he's not moving anywhere anytime soon. And a 86 average from a Coleman season suggests he not going to be a SuperCoach option in that time.
scShort: Remarkable comeback from the Coleman medallist and locked into the key forward role which limits his SuperCoach upside

scComment: The rebounding defender did his ACL last season, however is said to be progressing well and on track for a mid-season return. He can put up decent numbers in his half back role, however he'll need a while to get back in the groove and unlikely to make an impact this year.
scShort: Recovering from an ACL and on track for a mid-season return

scComment: Hogan is a different type of key forward. When at his best, he works hard up and down the ground and can put up numbers that make him Fantasy relevant (his 92 in 2018 would rank him 9th amongst current forwards this season). However, he's never looked the same player, and despite playing his best football last season since 2018, he's unlikely to push the top 6 in SuperCoach.
scShort: Best season since his 89 in 2028, however he still looks a long way off that player

scComment: After being used as a forward and midfielder in his early years, Blakey had a breakout season in 2022, playing as a dashing half back. He took over the kick-in duties from Jake Lloyd, which shows how much the Swans wanted the ball in his hands and they used him at every opportunity. With another year in the system and role, he should improve again in 2023, however I doubt it will be by enough to be a worthwhile selection.
scShort: Breakout season as a running defender but lack of marks and tackles limit him in SuperCoach

scComment: Dangerfield has been on a steady decline since 2017 when he was the number 1 man in SuperCoach. He bottomed out in 2022, averaging just 83 from decent enough centre bounce numbers, his first sub-100 season for 11 years. He demonstrated in the finals that he can still produce, averaging 115 from 50% CBAs. However, he's now 32 and Geelong have always taken a cautious approach with their older players, indicated by his 18 games last season at just 75% TOG. That, combined with his mid-only status, makes it hard to take the punt on him this season, despite his very cheap price tag.
scShort: As cheap as he's been for 11 years but lack of forward status and age makes it hard to do

scComment: The former top five draft pick had his best season in the AFL in 2022, playing all games as a lead up medium forward. It appears this will be his role going forward and I doubt a midfield move will come, which means outside his 101 average in the last five games of 2020, he'll be too hard to trust in SuperCoach.
scShort: Locked into medium forward role so unlikely to improve his average significantly

scComment: Ridley has the attributes to be an elite SuperCoach defender with his safe ball use (86%), high kick-to-handball ratio, intercept marking and spoils. He looked like an emerging top 6 defender after averaging 102 in 2020 as a 21-year-old and then coming hot out of the blocks in 2021, averaging 133 in the first 5 games. However, he hasnt hit those heights since. The intercept defender, who was the Bombers main distributor at the time, lost the majority of his kick-in duties and went from a loose marking defender who left his man at any opportunity to get involved and intercept, to a lock-down defender matching up on one of the opposition's dangerous forwards. There was hope he would return to the more SuperCoach-friendly role last season after Essendon landed Jake Kelly in the offseason, who plays that third tall defender role very well and could relieve Ridley of those defensive duties. While Kelly did this to some extent, the emergence of Redman meant that Ridley took a back seat in 2022, reducing his averaging 92. I think hes better than that and heading into his 7th season, he should be entering his peak. Redman is still the main man down there but Id be surprised if Ridley doesnt push back into the 100s this season, an potentially even higher.
scShort: Was on his way to being a top 6 defender before Redman emerged last season, but I think we'll see him bounceback to be a 100+ player

scComment: The former first round pick moved to Adelaide for more opportunities in 2021, however he has still found it hard to crack into the side. Hately has proven himself as a Fantasy scorer, averaging 113 AFL Fantasy points from 13 NEAFL games in 2019 and over 100 in the SANFL since arriving. He's obviously got some deficiencies in his game for him not to be selected on most weekends. As a mid-only with shaky job security, you can't be taking the risk with him in SuperCoach.
scShort: Has the pedigree but mid-only with shaky job security

scComment: The injury plagued mid has always been highly rated at the Lions and played the most games in his career in 2022 with 23. After coming into the season very cheaply priced, Berry started as an inside mid and looked to be a great mid-priced selection. However, he moved to a wing post-bye where he didnt looks as comfortable and only saw 5% CBAs. He was put back inside in a final and was best on ground and gave an indication we could see him spend more time in there this season. However, that was short lived when Dunkley arrived who will likely take up the main rotation with Neal and a combination of Rayner, Ashcroft, Bailey and Zorko, so I doubt well see Berry get the bump he needs.
scShort: Any chance of an inside mid move hurt by Dunkley coming, so will likely be a role player again in 2022

scComment: 3 seasons in and I still don't know whether Rowell is going to be a SuperCoach stud or dud. After record breaking numbers at junior level, Rowell exceeded everyone's expectations in his first few games at AFL level, averaging an adjusted 127 in his first 4. He then had a season ending shoulder injury while on 0 in Round 5. He didn't have any luck in year 2, with an early knee injury in Round 1 before returning to play the last 11 games but looked a shadow of himself, averaging 68 points per game but had excuses given the injury and low TOG of 55%. After a full preseason, he came out with a bang, scoring 157 in Round 1 and we all thought we were going to see the Matt Rowell promised to us in his debut season. This was short lived, averaging 84 the rest of the season. He plays completely inside with zero spread to get easy possession, highlighted by his 67% contested rate (top 8 mids 47%) incredibly low 1.2 marks per game (top 8 mids 4.3). He looked purely focused on his role which at times meant manning an opposition mid and winning the footy came second. The reports from the Suns were only positive though and he did was top 5 in the AFL for tackles, pressure acts and defensive half pressure acts. So maybe the role was just part of his development and he'll soon be unleased to win more of the footy. In year 4, he we should start to see him enter is peak, and if you asked me 4 years ago what I thought he'd be averaging I'd be confident it would be something over 110. If that were to be the case, he'd prove a terrific starting pick, but from what I saw in 2022, I highly doubt that now.
scShort: Outside of Round 1, he's yet to reach the heights of his junior days and debut season and I'm not confident that he'll reach that this year

scComment: Brad Hill has been disappointing since his move to the Saints. He reunites with Ross Lyon who was his coach during his career best footy and Lyon has already flagged a return to the wing for Hill. However, even his career best form won't be enough to challenge the top 6 defenders given his super low contested rate and lack of clearances, so he's not one to consider in SuperCoach.
scShort: A return to the wing and reuniting with Ross Lyon gives Hill hope of returning to his best footy but even that's not enough to be a top 6 defender

scComment: As outside as they come and a reason why wingmen aren't Fantasy relevant, highlighted by his 1.3 tackles per game. Only available in the midfield makes it less appealing.
scShort: Outside wingman with back-to-back seasons of regression

scComment: Greene has the potential to be a top 6 forward if unleashed, as he's shown in the past, he can be a prolific ball winner when playing in the midfield. However, he's also a very dangerous forward and as such has settled in that role. He can still push the 90-mark in such role, so theres some upside in his price, but not enough to consider in Classic unless we see him get 30%+ CBAs in the preseason.
scShort: Settled in the forward role where he can push the 80 mark but not the 100s when he's played midfield in the past

scComment: Howe finds himself at the Roos where he should see more than the 8 games he played for Hawks last season. Had had draft relevance in the past with defender status but as a mid-only, he's not one to consider in SuperCoach.
scShort: Now at the Roos but unlikely to make a SuperCoach impact as mid-only

scComment: Despite hitting great heights in real life as one of the best players in the AFL, Bolton is yet to take his SuperCoach scoring to that level given his high impact / low possession nature of his game. With the addition of Hopper and Taranto over the trade period, I expect we'll see Bolton play more as that dangerous forward who pinch hits in the midfield, rather than the vice versa. Therefore, I don't think he can increase his scoring to the level required to be a good selection.
scShort: High impact player who might play less midfield following the off season additions

scComment: Drew has become a regular in the Power midfield, playing 45 games in the last 2 seasons at approx. 60% CBAs. With the emergence of Rozee, Butters and addition of JHF, I wouldnt be surprised to see those numbers reduce in 2022 as Port try to be more dynamic in the midfield. Even if he does play and stay in the prominent midfield role, he's a pure inside midfielder and lacks the spread and easy possessions to make him a relevant option in Fantasy.
scShort: A regular in Ports midfield might find it harder this season with the emergence of the young stars

scComment: Graham appeared to be the next midfielder up once Cotchin, Prestia and Martin start to push out. And given his elite tackling ability and scoring at junior level, he's one I've kept an eye on. After 7 scores over 100 in 2021, including a massive 154, and 40% CBAs in the last 5, I expected that transition to happen last season. However, he went backwards, averaging 75 from just 22% CBAs and 48 from 1% in his last 5! He was 11th in line for season average CBAs at the Tigers in a clear sign that he might not be the next mid up. Couple that with the arrival of midfield duo Taranto and Hopper and I think Graham will remain as a high tackling forward. That should see him remain in the 70s and not make an impact in SuperCoach.
scShort: Arrival of Taranto and Hopper has quashed any hope of Graham stepping up in the midfield

scComment: For 3 years prior to last, Salem was as consistent as they come but just below the top 6, hovering around the 90 mark. He his injured knee in the first minutes of Round 1 on 5, forcing him to miss the next 10 games. He returned with an 83 then 104 and it looked like he'd continue to be that 90s player the rest of the season. However, he only managed 74 post bye as he lost kick-in duties (only 7% in last 5) and usage in defence, partly to Angus Brayshaw who took his rebound role when he was out and continued in it on return. He now comes into 2023 priced at 72 which is 26 less than what we know he can do. If AFL Fantasy, if he can produce around his best he'll be a great starting squad selection given he'll make enough cash and you have enough trades to upgrade later. However in limited trade formats, you'll probably need him to push over 100 to be a worthwhile selection and I'm not sure he can do that.
scShort: A poor year which saw him drop from the consistent 90 scorer of the past and if he can recapture that old form he's certainly one to consider

scComment: Former pick 11 played a career high 20 games in his second season at Essendon, averaging 80 points per game. I think he can play, he's just not in the first group of midfielders, being Parish, Shiel and Merrett, and with the recruitment of Setterfield and Hobbs expected to get more mid time, it's hard to bank on Caldwell increasing his workload in 2023.
scShort: Mid-only and no guarantee of mid-time makes it tough

scComment: 31-year-old key forward had some sort of resurgence in 2022, bumping his average up 21, despite 2 games at less than 50% game time. I doubt he can improve again though given his role and age so he's a pass in 2023.
scShort: 31-year-old key forward not a great combo

scComment: A decent ruck when given the opportunity but behind Draper in the pecking order and hasn't played more than 9 games in last 6 seasons. Can't have.
scShort: Hasn't played more than 9 games in last 6 seasons

scComment: The speedy halfback playted 22 games in 2022 after dealing with a serious ankle injury in 2021. He started to show the talent displayed early in his career and had somewhat of a breakout to end the season with 94 post bye and 111 in the last 5 games. On those numbers he presents some value at a 84 price tag, but I do find it hard to pick a defender to average 100+ (which you'd need) when he's probably 3rd in line behind Dale and Daniel. One for Draft but too risky in Classic for me.
scShort: 94 post bye and 111 in the last 5 games a good sign heading into 2023, but still behind Dale and Daniel in pecking order

scComment: Has played a vital role as a hard running small forward at West Coast for a number of years now, just not a great role for SuperCoach scoring.
scShort: Hard running small forward not one for SuperCoach

scComment: He's one of the good guys of footy and had some SuperCoach relevance in his time, but I was surprised with the amount of opportunity he got last year over the development of the youngsters (21 games at 53% CBAs). I doubt we see him get those chances under Clarko.
scShort: Might find it hard for opportunities this season

scComment: Returned to the midfield rotation post bye with 31% CBAs after just 9% pre, but that didn't yield much of a bump in scoring. Even with forward status, I doubt he'll come into SuperCoach relevance in 2023.
scShort: 77 post bye despite 31% CBAs which I doubt he'll see in 2023

scComment: The star small forward has been used in the midfield for burst over the past 4 seasons, but his scoring manages to stay in the low 70s. I see no reason why that will change this year.
scShort: 67-74 for 4 seasons and hard to see that changing

scComment: One of my favourite players and one who I thought we might see unleashed into the midfield one day. After preseason match-sim vision last year, it looked like 2022 was going to be the year. However, it never eventuated. He did start a few games inside towards the end of the year (13% CBA last 5) but it was only for an intimidation / impact reason then he'd move back to defence. He's averaged 97 before as a defender and went 92 post bye, botha lot more than what he's priced at heading into 2023. However, at low ownership and 97 still not enough to be a top 6 defender, there's too much risk with that. I'm still holding hope of a midfield switch which would rocket him into calculations, but for now he's just a watch.
scShort: Priced 14 less than his best but needs an unlikley midfield move to be considered

scComment: I've been a fan of the former top 10 pick for a few years now. He has a SuperCoach game that I think will see him be a top six defender before his career is done. 90 post bye in 2022 was a good sign heading into his age 24 season. The ball will be back there a lot this season so Ive got a watch on him, but I wouldnt be brave enough to start him.
scShort: 90 post bye and should see a lot of looks this season which might push him into the 100s

scComment: Talented forward had his most consistent season to date including 102 in last 5, but still not enough to be in discussions in SuperCoach.
scShort: Max average 82 in 11 season rules him out

scComment: Bonner has had flashes of good scores throughout his career, however he's never put together a full season. Port have many similar off the half back line and will likely be on the fringe again this season. Pass.
scShort: Flashes of good scores but always on the fringe so hard to trust
A handy scorer for a key defender helped by 76% of kick-in duties, but still not enough to make him relevant in SuperCoach

scComment: After seeing consistent midfield minutes in his debut season with 31% CBAs in the first half, Jordon took up a wing role in 2023 left vacant by Brayshaw moving to a half back. He played an important role for the team, playing 22 games at an average of 75. However, as a mid-only, 0% CBAs is not what you want for decent SuperCoach prospects. Maybe one for the future but not while the Dees' midfield is stacked.
scShort: Moved to a wing which will limit his output while the Dees' mids are stacked
Scores better than most key position players on the back of his seven marks per game, but thats still not enough to be relevant in Fantasy

scComment: Fiorini has always shown the ability to find the ball, however has struggled for regular games, with the knock on him being he's not very damaging by foot and a bit one paced. He was forced to apply his trade in the VFL for most of the year where he averaged a whopping 135 AFL Fantasy points. The selection and role risk is probably too much to wear, despite his low price.
scShort: Can find the ball in the right role but out of favour at the Suns which makes him too hard to trust

scComment: The number 7 pick of the 2021 draft came with big wraps, some saying he was the most ready-made after Daicos. After a 124 from 65% CBAs in the AAMI on low TOG, the wraps looked true. However, he took a while to find his feet, averaging 50 pre bye on low game time. However, he looked more and more comfortable as the season went on, averaging 78 post bye but 89 in AFL Fantasy, meaning he was winning enough footy, just not scoring in SuperCoach. He did this with 28% CBAs, which you expect will skyrocket after the trading of O'Meara and Mitchell opening up plenty of midfield opportunities at the developing Hawks where it's very apparent Sam Mitchell is keen to get as many minutes into his kids as possible. This will see his contested rate jump from the low 32% in 2022 and hopefully bring about higher SC scoring. 2nd year breakouts are rare, but when they pay off, they can be competition winning, as per Oliver in 2017 (70 to 112). I don't think Ward can reach these heights and it's likely too big of a risk to start with him, but I'm keeping my eye on him for Round 3 trades should he start the season with a bang.
scShort: 2nd year breakouts are rare but there will be ample midfield opportunity with Mitchell and O'Meara gone, so Ward has every chance to do so

scComment: Goldstein has been a great SuperCoach ruckman of the past and it took until his 16th season for him to take a back seat and let a younger ruck take control. He was still used in 66% of North's CBAs post bye at an average of 93, but this was well down from his 78% and 87% of the years prior. I'm not sure how Clarko will run it but even if Goldy remains a key pillar of their ruck setup, I doubt he'll improve on his average now he's 34.
scShort: Roos have begun to look at life after Goldy and I expect his reduced role and scoring to continue in 2023

scComment: Not sure theres a harder player to get a read on that Jaidyn Stephenson, in real life and in Fantasy. After showing glimpses of his early Collingwood days in his first year at the Roos, which included going over 110 3 times, including a monster 153, he took a step back in 2022. He looked a shadow of himself, and failed to reach 70 in over half of his games. He finished the season in the backline and while he was found out at times defensively, he provided some run and looked at his best, averaging 85 points in his last 5 with 28% kick-ins. Priced at 71, theres upside there if he can keep that up in 2023. However, a new coach and game style brings even more unknown to the inconsistent Stephenson, so youd be a brave coach to consider starting him.
scShort: Looked his best in defence with 85 in last 5 but who knows what Clarko will do with him in 2023

scComment: Jackson arrives at Fremantle after 3 seasons at the Dees where he played forward and backed up Max Gawn in the ruck. He has all the attributes to be a star Fantasy ruck one day, with his follow up work and tackle pressure as good as any at his age. When given the shot to lead the ruck, Jackson gave us a taste what what's to come, with a 137 from 67% CBAs when Gawn was out and his 4 scores over 120 came from 47% in the ruck compared to his season average of 37%. Unfortunately, he's landed at a destination with another gun young ruckman and it's likely he'll play second fiddle to Darcy in the ruck this season. It's been floated that Jackson could be used in a Blicavs-like tall midfielder role, but even if that eventuates this year, I doubt he can push his average up towards the 100-mark needed for him to be a good pick at his price, without having more than 50% of the ruck time. One for the future, but unlikely to be this year.
scShort: Arrives at Freo and will likely play second fiddle again which will delay his inevitable SuperCoach breakout
A switch to defence saw Battle have a career best season and put up some nice numbers, but not enough to be a relevant SuperCoach defender

scComment: Buddy at his peak was a rare case of being Fantasy relevant as a key forward. He's now 36 though, so despite having the odd big game, you can't rely on him in Fantasy.
scShort: 36-year-old key forward not what you want in SuperCoach

scComment: Gun small forward who saw some centre bounce action in 2022 with 31% CBAs, but that was purely as an impact and he drifted back forward after the bounce. He managed 89 post bye which is great for a small forward, but small forwards are never good SuperCoach options, even the best small forward in the game.
scShort: One of the best small forwards in the comp but still not one for SuperCoach

scComment: Actually beat his Coleman season by 1 point per game, but it shows key forwards are not what you want in your SuperCoach team.
scShort: Gun key forward, just not SuperCoach relevant
Star key forward, not in SuperCoach though

scComment: Finlayson had a career best season in his first at the Power, boosting his average by 15 points to 83. It was largely on the back of Lycett going down, meaning he was forced to be their primary ruck for the second half of the season. He had 65% CBAs and 71% in his last 5 games, which will return to the normal 10-20% this season which Lycett back. His average will likely follow suit.
scShort: Career high average helped by Lycett going down and will likely return to the 60-70 mark on his return

scComment: Sidebottom has been a SuperCoach gun of the past, but now takes a much lesser role at the Pies, splitting his time between wing and half forward and rarely seeing centre bounces (just 3% in 2022). As a mid-only in 2023, he's unlikely to make an impact if he remains in his outside role. Ignore the discount to career high.
scShort: Now a wingman and 32 and not in the role that once made him a SuperCoach gun

scComment: Stengle was another feel-good story of 2022, winning a premiership and making the All Australian team after being delisted by the Crows. He also produced career best SuperCoach numbers, with a 77 average proving a great buy for owners last year. However, small forwards cap out at about the 70-80 mark for the elite, so it's unlikely we'll see any further growth from here.
scShort: Career best season making the AA team, but small forwards generally cap out at the 70 mark

scComment: The former top 10 pick found a role on the wing in 2022 and played a career high 19 games after just 6 in the prior 2 seasons. Hes never been much of a scorer, even at VFL level, and at mid-only and the arrival of Blake Acres on a wing, OBrien wont make an impact in SuperCoach this year.
scShort: Found a home on the wing in 2022 but with Acres arriving he might find it hard to hold his spot

scComment: The fan-favourite can score when given the chance, as indicated by his 114 AFL Fantasy points at VFL level last season. However has never played more than 13 games in a season in his 7 year career. Doubt he'll beat that figure this season given the inclusion of Dunkley to the Lions' 22.
scShort: Can score okay but never played more than 13 games in 7 years

scComment: Close has done well to become a regular in a very strong team after being taken as a rookie 3 years ago. He's limited to a role player up forward, so he's not an option in SuperCOach.
scShort: Role player who has been great for Geelong but not one for SuperCoach

scComment: Sloane unfortunately did his ACL early last season. He's on track for an early year recovery, however at 33 and more time given to the kids, I doubt we'll see him make an impact this year.
scShort: 33 and fresh off an ACL

scComment: Bailey has something special about him and looks to be a future star of the comp. However, he might be one of those who are better in real life than in SuperCoach, showcased by his sub-80 average last season, despite having big impact in some games. The Lions need someone like him to take the next step into the midfield, but that might be halted by the arrival of Dunkley. I expect his scoring and CBA role to still increase in 2022, however not enough to take a punt on in Classic.

I've been waiting for a Fisher breakout as Carlton have used him in centre bounces throughout his career and he's always spoken of highly by key members of the team. However, the breakout is yet to eventuate and he played just 13 games last season without making much of an impact. With the Blues' 22 getting stronger, I think he might struggle again in 2023.
scShort: Just 13 games last season and might struggle again

scComment: Key forward whose development surprised me last season as he started to take over some games. His average of 70 is great for a key forward, and given hes just 24 he could improve again. However, I doubt it will ever be enough to make an impact in Fantasy.
scShort: Strong season by the key forward but scoring will be capped

scComment: Baker does a bit of everything for the Tigers, playing forward, back and even in the middle. He can excel at all of them and if we know he was going to remain as a defender or a mid then we might be able to trust him in SuperCoach. However, his role is too hard to read and given his likely very low ownership numbers, he's too much of a risk to consider.
scShort: He can play but too hard to predict what role he will play week-to-week

scComment: Became an important role player for the Blues. He's a bit of a fix-it player and even spent some time in the ruck, attending 14% of CBAs. This brings about a bump in scoring, but not enough to consider in SuperCoach.
scShort: Role player for the Blues not in SuperCoach calculations

scComment: Off-season surgery meant the former first rounder played just 10 games last season after 21 the year prior. Hinkley has flagged midfield time for him in 2022, which unsurprisingly didnt eventuate. May become relevant again in the future, but I doubt that will be this season.
scShort: Just 10 games last year and didn't do a heap in the reserves
Genuine role player in defence who has capped out at the 70 mark

scComment: Chapman has showed great signs in his first two seasons and certainly looks like one for the future. His intercept marking and long arms are a feature and should bode well for SuperCoach scoring. Theres talk of him one day moving to a wing or even inside, but for now it looks like hell be applying his craft as a defender. While he certainly has the attributes to score, hes behind Young and Ryan for distribution and its likely hell have another year in the 70/80s before we see him take the next step.
scShort: Very impressive first 2 seasons but behind the pecking order in defence so will need to wait before the breakout

scComment: Williams has been disappointing since his move to the Blues - for Carlton fans and Fantasy coaches. He was a popular mid-priced pick in 2021 following a change of clubs for more midfield time after averaging 108 in the second half of 2019 in a midfield role. After string of poor performances, he was banished from the midfield and played in defence. That defence role continued to last season before he badly injured his calf, missing the majority of the season. He enters 2023 priced about 15 less than what he can produce in a defensive role and 30 less in a midfield role. In the limited trade format, you'd need him to be closer to that 30-mark to be a worthwhile pick. I think his midfield role is over, but I'm still not discounting him to produce decent numbers this year in defence.
scShort: Calf injury ruined 2022 and unless he moves back into the midfield it's unlikely he'll scorer enough to be relevant

scComment: Star forward, however has only been around the mid-70 mark in Fantasy across his career. It's about all you can expect from a small forward and that seems to be about his limit.
scShort: Star small forward but scoring limited to sub-80

scComment: McGovern will be looking to bounce back after a few disappointing seasons. He's always been a much better player in real life than in SuperCoach, demonstrated by his career best season of 93 points per game despite his elite intercept marking ability, so he's not an option in SuperCoach.
scShort: Hopefully stays on the park this year but even at his best hasn't been much of a SuperCoach player

scComment: After averaging 80 in the last 5 games of 2021 and 127 in the AAMI, it looked like McInerney was going to breakout last season and that the wing/half back role left vacent by Jordan Dawson. However, he was one of the few young Swans who didn't improve, averaging just 69 for the year. The breakout may come this season, but at mid-only and lack of CBAs (3% last season compared to 13% in 2021), he's not worth taking the punt on in SuperCoach.
scShort: Let a few down last year and now only available in the midfield

scComment: So far in his career, Scott has played wing, a half forward, as a tagger and then finally settled as a defender in 2023 where he can career highs in scoring and games played. He looks like he could become a decent player, but who knows what Clarko will do and Scott's role and position in the team are unknown.
scShort: Career high in scoring and games played after shifting to defence, but not what how Clarko will use him in 2023

scComment: The former number 11 pick has been a regular for the Swans since his second season, playing over 21 games per season since. I thought he was a breakout candidate in 2020 after averaging 90 points in his final five games of 2019, however he's stagnated from there. This is on the back of a big drop in CBAs, where he took 69% in the first half of 2020 yet only 2% in the second half of 2022. Looks like the new Swans youngsters have overtaken him and its likely hell remain in defence.
scShort: Pushed out of the midfield which reduces his upside

scComment: Wright has been great for the Bombers since arriving in 2021, topped off by his B&F win last year. However, a 78 average in a B&F year shows you how capped key forwards are for Fantasy scoring.
scShort: 78 average in a B&F year shows you how capped key forwards are for Fantasy scoring

scComment: Setterfield has shown promise throughout his career, from being a top five pick, to big NEAFL numbers, to averaging 104 in the second half of 2020 with decent CBA numbers. However, he struggled for consistency and games at the Blues, not reaching 65 in either season despite averaging 107 AFL Fantasy points at VFL level. He now finds himself at the Bombers who are crying out for a tall midfielder and there's a chance he steps right in and plays his preferred role. As a mid-only option, it's too risky to take a punt on him priced at 63. But I have a feeling he'll beat that price by a fair bit.
scShort: Hopefully gets more inside opportunity at the Dons

scComment: Bowes was a prolific midfielder in juniors, averaging 118 AFL Fantasy points in the NAB League which saw him be a top 10 pick at the Suns. He played predominantly in defence at AFL level looked to breakout as a Fantasy gun, averaging 104 in the first 8 games of 2021, taking the majority of the kick-ins in that time. He then injured his hamstring and played a less prominent role when he returned and finished the year with an 83 average. That made him a potential underpriced option last season, before shoulder surgery in the preseason ruled him out for the first 4 months of the year. From there things got a bit weird. He played just the 5 games and spend a lot of time in the VFL, where he averaged 92 Fantasy points. He was then offloaded to Geelong in what will go down as the worst trade in history, with him and pick 7 going to Geelong for a future 3rd pick #salarydump. Geelong said they were keen to land him, but it's unknown if they wanted him of the pick 7 attached. He struggled for games at the Suns and it will be tougher to break into the reigning premiers' 22, but if he is named in Round 1 and performs in the preseason, he's still the talented player who averaged in the 100s for a large part of 2021.
scShort: Might find it hard for opportunity at the Cats but has displayed a SuperCoach game in the past so remains a preseason watch

scComment: Now established as the Cats number 1 ruck, but a career best of 98 and fresh off an 80, hes not going to be the ruck you want to own in SuperCoach.
scShort: Now 32 and fresh off an 80

scComment: The mature aged recruit, who came into the AFL with some great numbers in the SANFL (109 AFL Fantay average in 2018), hasnt missed a beat since arriving at the Saints, only missing 3 games in 4 years. His role is different to when he was in the SANFL, he plays more of a defensive role at the Saints which limits his value in SuperCoach.
scShort: A consistent role player at the Saints

scComment: The 2021 SSP selection burst onto the scene in a terrific role off a half back flank, finishing his first season averaging 76. However, the momentum was halted with a stress fracture in the preseason practice match, delaying his start to the 2022 season. He managed 9 matches at an average of 64, well down on his debut season. His VFL numbers werent great either, so I think he struggled with the delayed start. Hell be better in 2023 with a full preseason, but at this price and role, hes not worth the risk.
scShort: Disappointing 2022 after promising debut season, should bounce back

scComment: After a career best 91 in 2021, Hardwick returned to the 70s type defender in 2022. He did average 85 post bye when his kick-ins went from 28% to 39%, but with so many distributors at the Hawks, including Sicily, Bramble and Scrimshaw, I think he will remain in this range from now on, unless something happens to Sicily as it did in 2021.
scShort: Regressed with Sicily back but post bye showed he can still go 85+

scComment: If you had asked me after his 2nd season where Clark would be heading into his 6th, I would've said he'd be a top 6 defender by now and if not defender, then he'd certainly have midfield status. The former top 10 pick had 2x 110+ scores in his last 7 matches was heavily involved in centre bounces. He hasn't come on from there, averaging 81, 74 and 57 in the 3 years since and seen less and less time in the midfield. Hes also had a shocking run of luck, none more so than last season. He had shoulder surgery after a preseason match when he was getting CBAs and looking good, forcing him to miss the first 13 rounds and then had surgery again on a nasal fracture from a sickening clash in Round 16. Hes due for some luck and a chance in coach might see him finally unleashed into the midfield. Priced at 57, I certainly think he's one to consider if that midfield role is there.
scShort: Due for some luck and has the ability so a big role watch in the preseason

scComment: Noble has become a regular in defence for the Pies after being picked up in the mid-season draft of 2019. He's a 70-75 guy, which is respectable but not enough to be relevant in SuperCoach.
scShort: 70-75 guy which is not enough to be relevant in SuperCoach

scComment: Flynn is part of the ruck merry-go-round at the Giants and managed 24 games in the past 2 seasons, averaging in the mid-80s. He's displayed some talent, I just don't want to deal with the GWS rucks.
scShort: Looks good when playing but can't trust the Giants ruck setup

scComment: Hickey has been a sensational get by the Swans. However, he still only manages to rank 12th amongst rucks for average and at 32, its hard to see that average increasing.
scShort: At 32 unlikley to be a top 10 ruck

scComment: Dixon has a pretty good scoring history in SuperCoach thanks to his elite contested marking ability. He's hovered around the top 15 forwards for the past 3 seasons and while he can reach this mark again, I doubt we'll see him break the 100 mark and contend with the top 6.
scShort: 32-year-old key forward who tops out at the 90 mark

scComment: McIntosh has a career high average of 80 heading into his 11th season. His outside role limits him from pushing up to triple figures and becoming a relevant SuperCoach option.
scShort: Outside wing with mid-only not what you want

scComment: Averaged 105 post bye when he took a more prominent role with McGovern out, resulting in a career high 93 average. McGovern is back fit and he'll lose some opportunity back there, so I think he goes back to his 80s in 2023.
scShort: Key defender who got a bump with McGovern out

scComment: ANB is a genuine role player in the Melbourne forward line. Very valuable for the Dees, not so much for SuperCoach.
scShort: Very valuable for the Dees, not so much for SuperCoach

scComment: One of the best young defenders in the comp and that became well known in 2022 when he took out All Australian honours. He put up some decent SuperCoach scoring on the back of his elite intercept rate (9.5 v 7.2 of the top 6 defenders) and at just 23, he'll improve his reputation again in 2023. However, we rarely see key defenders push the top 6 in SuperCoach so I doubt he'll be relevant in 2023.
scShort: Gun young key defender but not one for SuperCoch

scComment: Ladhams moved to Sydney for more opportunities, however didn't get them, playing just the 11 games for the season. He's shown he can score well in the sole ruck role and averaged 102 AFL Fantasy points in the VFL last year, but Hickey still appears the main man at the Swans and I doubt we'll see Ladhams push his average at AFL level up to the 100+ mark required.
scShort: Still behind Hickey and needs to be the sole ruck to score

scComment: Seedsman had a career best season on a wing in 2021 but sadly hasnt played since due to concussion. Hes now on the rookie list and weve had no indication that hell play again. Even if he does play and with his discount, hes still a pass as a mid-only.
scShort: Dealing with concussion issues and now on the inactive list

scComment: An ankle injured and stress fracture in his foot meant that Sheed played just 1 game last season. He gets a discount which means he enters 2023 priced at 60. Hes never been a damaging SuperCoach player, highlighted by his 83 average from 66% CBAs in 2021, however at that price he must be considered. In his 1 game in 2022, he had 88% CBAs, which is an indication Simpson wants to use him as an inside mid, rather than the wing/half forward role hes played for a lot of his career. If he plays an inside role in 2023, he can certainly push the 85-90 mark which certainly wouldn't make him a keeper, but would make make enough cash to be a worthwhile mid-priced selection. Keep an eye on his CBAs in the preseason for confirmation.
scShort: Big discount after 1 game last year and if he can keep those CBAs up he can bounce back to the 90s

scComment: After becoming a regular in the Swans' backline, Cunningham was limited to just 9 games in 2022 due to an abdominal injury and form. I had some decent homes for him to fill the void left by Dawson, given his booming kick and 27% KI rate in the last 5 games of 2021, however Blakey ended up taking that slack. Priced at 56, there's a bit of value there given he's gone 80 in the past. But with 0% KIs last year, it's not a good sign.
scShort: Still has potential but just 9 games last year and 0% KI not a good sign

scComment: Farrell is known for his booming left foot and Port Adelaide like to use that weapon on the wing and forward of the ball to create deep opportunities. He returned from an ACL in 2022 and had a career best SuperCoach season, averaging 73. Youd think hell see more opportunity in 2023 with Amon leaving on a wing, but as a mid-only option, you cant have him in SuperCoach.
scShort: Could see more opportunity with Amon leaving, but not as a mid-only option

scComment: Jiath broke out in 2022, bumping his average by 35 points to finish with 84. He backed it up with a 78 which suggests that 80-mark is about his limit. He has even more impact in real life with his intercept ability being as good as any in the comp. It's hard to see Jiath coming into the SuperCoach relevance conversation again.
scShort: The 80-mark appears his limit
Has talent but hovered around the 60-mark for his 6 seasons in the AFL

scComment: A tall forward who scores his best when playing ruck, however doesnt like playing there. English will take the lion share anywhere so Lobbs ruck time is limited. Pass.
scShort: Scores okay in the ruck but will spend most his time forward now at the Dogs

scComment: After sitting behind Goldstein for many years, Xerri finally got his chance in 2022, playing 12 matches at 50% CBAs. He looked good at time too, with his contested marking and follow-up work a feature. Goldy is still around and I'm not sure how Clarko will play it, but with Coleman-Jones also there I doubt we'll see much more than the 50% ruck time Xerri got last season. He has shown he can dominate at the VFL level, averaging 105 AFL Fantasy points in 2021, I just think we'll Goldy gone before we see Xerri hit his straps at AFL level.
scShort: Got his chance in 2022 but it's crowded in the rucks at North so hard to see him increasing

scComment: After just 6 games in his second season, Stephens played 15 games on a wing for the Swans. The former top 5 pick may one day move into the midfield, but as a mid-only who gets 0% CBAs, there's not enough upside to select him this season.
scShort: Has potential but mid-only and 0% CBAs makes it tough
A decent scorer in the past, Dumont is a depth player for Port and not one to consider

scComment: Howe's 2020 season is an obvious anomaly, given it's his only one over 95 in 12 seasons. The short quarters and 4 matches may have had something to do with it, but he did look unstoppable in those 4 games. Since then, he has resumed more of a shutdown role on an opposition dangerous forward. He's also lost a lot of kicks to Daicos and even Maynard and Quaynor who have stepped up the last 2. Ignore the discount to career high, he's not that SuperCoach player anymore.
scShort: Ignore the discount to career high, he plays a more defensive role nowadays

scComment: Guthrie played a career high 21 games for Geelong in 2022, cementing his spot in the team and winning a premiership. He had some nice scoring games when Geelong switched to a kick-mark play and when Stewart was missing, but I doubt hell ever average enough to be considered in SuperCoach.
scShort: Now a regular for the Cats but not one for SuperCoach

scComment: A PCL injury kept Pittonet to 8 games in 2022. During that time, De Koning took over as number 1 ruck and looked great, so I'm not sure how much ruck Pittonet will play in 2023.
scShort: Might have lost the number 1 spot to De Koning which will make it tough
Struggled for games since being drafted and scoring to date in the AFL hasn't been great

scComment: A career best year in defence from the 24-year-old even had some calling for All Australian. A 81 average is about what to expect from decent key defenders, so he's not one for SuperCoach.
scShort: 81 in a close-to-All Australian year

scComment: Zak Jones has progressed from a half back flanker to a wingman to an inside midfielder, where he provided something different to the plethora of inside mids (Steele, Ross, Brad Crouch). He played the role pretty well in 2021, averaging 93 highlighted by a 153 and 123 in consecutive weeks. He never hit those heights last season though, averaging 64 from diminishing CBAs after taking indefinite leave to start the season. Not sure what role Ross Lyon will give him but if its a 50%+ CBA one like 2020 and 2021 then he could certainly bump his average by 20 and provide some value as a starting squad member, but in limited trade you probably need more than that.
scShort: Looking to bounce back from 64 in an interrupted year after 93 the season prior

scComment: Sharman has an impressive set of hands, but has only played 13 games since being taken in the 2021 mid-season draft. Plays as a 3rd tall and tried in defence, but havent seen enough to think hes going to be a Fantasy option, despite his 20 point discount to his debut season.
scShort: Still finding his feet at AFL level

scComment: Not many half back flankers are taken as a top four pick, so Ash obviously has the talent. He showed some of that talent in 2021, particularly in the first half of the season when he had kick-in duties and averaged 88 points per game - highlighted by a 139 against the Pies. In an odd shift by Leon Cameron, he's since been playing in the midfield, at times as a tagger, a wingman and others just as a pure mid ahead of the more proven types. That means he's got midfield only status, ruling him out of selection in SuperCoach. I imagine he'll move back to half back this season and get defender status to hopefully one day become the stud defender expected of him on draft night.
scShort: Hopefully moves his natural half back position
Just 7 games from the key defender in 2022

scComment: Highly rated small defender who has become a regular for the Lions, often taking the opposition's number one medium forward. It's not a role for producing decent Fantasy scores though and he's not relevant this season.
scShort: Very good small defender but not a scorer

scComment: Taylor has become a regular for the Roos and has a bit about him. I think he'll become a good player, however his role (defensive half forward) will keep him around the 60 mark when playing.
scShort: Defensive half forward role will keep him around the 60 mark
Gun pressure forward for Fremantle, not the role for SuperCoach scoring though

scComment: A defensive midfielder who saw 1% CBAs for the season after being a staple there for over 10 years. With Hawks looking to give time to their kids, hes moved to the Roos where he will reunite with Clarko. I do think hell play more of an off-field leadership role, but if Clarko does give him high CBAs in the preseason, he could be an interesting option in the forward line priced at 57, 36 less than his best.
scShort: Likely to take a step back at the Roos but still worth seeing how it plays out given price and position

scComment: After a fairy-tale debut and then being the most popular pick in SuperCoach in 2020, Pickett has found himself on the wing at the Tigers in a very team-first role. With mid-only status and coming off a 72 average, its hard to make a case for him.
scShort: Mid-only status and coming off a 72

scComment: The former number one draft pick returned from an ACL last season to play all 24 games, averaging 69 points. So far in his career, he's been more of an impact player than an accumulator, which is never a great thing for SuperCoach scoring. We've all been waiting for him to pop and be the explosive, goal kicking mid the Lions are crying out for. Coming back from a knee is never smooth sailing, so we can excuse him for his low output in 2022. However, the fact that his CBAs reduced as the year went on isn't a great sign. Dunkley arriving will take some CBAs away, but I still think they need to allocate a spot for one of Bailey, Rayner and Zorko, so I still expect him to get a small bump in midfield minutes. That's not enough to make him relevant in SuperCoach though based on his output to date.
scShort: Still waiting for the breakout and CBAs reducing as the season went on isn't a good sign
4 uninterrupted seasons at the Lions and 60-70 is what we can expect

scComment: Saw some opportunity with the depleted West Coast team last season, playing 18 games for a career high 64. Showed enough signs to suggest he might stay in when theyre full strength. I cant see him ever been a prominent scorer though.
scShort: Might find it tougher with a full strength West Coast

scComment: Lukosius returned to the forward-line in 2022 after looking great as a running defender the year prior. His SuperCoach output felt it, dropping 15 points per game. If he remains a forward, then you can rule him out of calculations. If he moves back to defence, where he showed shades of a young Lachie Whitfield, he'll get a nice bump in scoring and potential DPP, but still not enough to make him an option in SuperCoach.
scShort: Flopped in his return to the forward-line and can bounce back if he moves back to defence

scComment: Holmes had a fantastic 2nd season, taking a prominent role on a wing and even spent some time inside for the eventual premiers. His scoring didnt reflect his impact, but his 74 post bye and 84 last 5 was about right. I think he can reproduce that level in year 3, which is not enough to consider as a mid-only.
scShort: Great season but even his 94 in last 5 isn't enough to consider as mid-only

scComment: At his peak, Walters could be a damaging midfielder, as demonstrated by his 112 points per game to start the 2020 season (from 64% of CBAs). However, with Serong and Brayshaw stepping up, the 32-year-old is now used solely as a small forward (1% CBAs in 2022). He's not worth considering.
scShort: Now a pure small forward with 0% CBAs
