scComment: Small lockdown defender returned from an ACL to play 9 games in 2022 before doing it again. We wish him all the best in recovery.
scShort: ACL for the second time last season

scComment: After a very impressive first season, Bowey looked like he was going to take another step with a 151 in Round 2 and backed it up with a 89. While he maintained the role, he didnt reproduce that output and eventually found himself out of the side towards the end of the season. Hes showed enough to suggest hes going to be a gun in the future, but hes behind a few at the Dees so it wont be for a few years yet.
scShort: Was out of the side at the end of the season and behind a few at the Dees for usage

scComment: An intercept defender was forced to play more of a lockdown role with all the injuries at the Blues. He was a fringe player before then and I imagine him to be on the edge again this season.
scShort: Got opportunity with all the injuries last year but might struggle now

scComment: Mitch Lewis announced himself in 2022 as a star key forward of the comp. But even the best key forwards cap out at the 80 mark, so that's about max for him.
scShort: Gun key forward but limited in SuperCoach
Become a regular but career best of just 81 in 11 seasons rules him out

scComment: Stringer had a disappointing season after a career best 2021. A groin injury in the preseason saw his midfield minutes drop from 69% CBAs the year prior to 37%, but even when he was in there, he looked far from the 110-averaging player from the second half of 2021. Both Worsfold and Rutten liked using him in the middle but with a new coach, Stringers role is up in the air. As is his fitness, which is also never stable. Hes a pass for me, despite the obvious upside.
scShort: Disappointing 2022 after a career best 2021 - form, fitness and role too hard to predict
Small forward that has missed a lot of footy due to various injuries

scComment: Was very impressive in his debut season, averaging 55 from a wing but kept getting better as the year went on. Mid-only wingmen aren't are great combo in SuperCoach, add in a 2nd year player and it's a no for me, but hopefully he goes on with it.
scShort: Impressive wingman with a bright future but mid-only rules him out

scComment: Sparrow has been getting midfield opportunities in a strong midfield since his debut. The scoring hasn't followed suit, averaging 67 from 32% CBAs. He's obviously highly rated, however he'll likely continue in a forward-mid role for the time being while the big boys are still there, and I doubt we will see his scoring spike much more than 80. Pass.
scShort: Mid-forward who gets CBAs but yet to show a scoring game

scComment: Ross has shown a bit when given the opportunity and dominated at reserve level (116 AFL Fantasy average in 2021 and 99 in 2022) so I think he's got potential to belong at AFL level at one point. However, as a SuperCoach option, he's not a very attractive one at that price, mid-only and with Taranto and Hopper entering the fold.
scShort: Going to find it hard with Taranto and Hopper

scComment: A crazy debut season for JHF. Outside of all the noise, I thought he showed more than enough on field in a struggling side and so much going on off field. He saw 40% CBAs in his first year which I doubt he'll meet at Port given their more seasoned midfield group. He's a pass for me, but as we know about 2nd year breakouts, it's not too late to jump on after 2 or 3 rounds if they look the real deal.
scShort: Doubt he'll see the 40% CBAs at Port, but should get more looks in a stronger team

scComment: Sholl finished 2020 with an adjusted 111 and 90 and was the designated kicker at the Crows. He then had a 160, 103 and 91 in his first five games of 2021 and looked to be a serious player of the future. It all went downhill from there and Sholl has struggled for senior opportunities since. I've seen enough to believe he'll be a player in the future, but as a midfield only option in Fantasy he's not an option this year.
scShort: Wing with mid-only status yet to cement his spot in the team

scComment: Curnow signed a 1 year contract after not playing a game in 2022. The much loved veteran provides great leadership and depth to the Blues, but I doubt the 33-year-old will be in their best 22 this season.
scShort: No games last year and could be the same again

scComment: Darling missed the entire preseason which meant he had a slow start to 2022, averaging 65 in the first half. This increased to 76 in his last 5, which is a more accurate reflection of where he's been the past 5 seasons. I expect him to be around that mark in 2023, which is well below the level required to be SuperCoach relevant.
scShort: 76 in last 5 is about what to expect
34-year-old key forward isn't what you want in your SuperCoach side

scComment: With Pittonet out with injury for a lot of 2022, De Koning got his chance, playing 19 games for the season at 70% CBAs. He impressed with his leap and marking ability, however didn't make much of an impact in scoring, averaging 75 for the year. He's never been much of a scorer though, even in juniors (69 AFL Fantasy points) and at VFL level (59). He should show progress with natural improvement, however it won't be enough to warrant starting with him in Classic.
scShort: Now the number 1 ruck but never been a scorer

scComment: Hollands finally got his chance in Round 19 after being drafted pick 7 two years prior and didn't disappoint. He played on a wing and certainly didn't look out of place, even scoring 116 in one game. He's only available in the midfield this year which dampens any chance of him making an impact in SuperCoach this season. But one for the future if he ever moves inside or gets forward status.
scShort: Looked great in 5 games but mid-only rules him out this year

scComment: Schoenberg has slowly increased his midfield role, from 18% CBAs in 2020, 35% in 2021, 38% in the first half of 2022 and then 56% to finish. However, his scoring output hasn't chanced, hovering around the 60-70 mark throughout. He's highly rated at the Crows and will likely be part of their main midfield brigade in 2023 alongside Laird and Berry, but until we see a scoring ceiling, he's going to be irrelevant in SuperCoach.
scShort: Getting more looks in the middle but scoring is yet to pop
The star key forward of the future will miss the start of the season with a shoulder reconstruction
Debuted in 2022 and looked great on a wing, but now as mid-only won't make a Fantasy impact this year

scComment: A 2021 mid-season draftee saw some midfield opportunities in 2022 given the injuries to their prime moves and averaged 60 points. With most of the cattle coming back, I doubt he'll see those chances again and he's not an option in SuperCoach.
scShort: Might struggle for opportunities in a full strength West Coast team

scComment: The Irishman is a favourite of Mitchells, who used his strong tackle ability in centre bounces, attending 42% for the season. Like fellow Irishmen, he'll continue to get better, but a 62 average last season indicates he's not going to be a Fantasy scorer.
scShort: Used in centre bounces last year but average remained modest
Fallen out of favour at the Suns after averaging 82 in 2019

scComment: Impey dropped 29 points from his 2021 average, despite his favourable defender role. Even if he bounces back to the 90s, the upside isn't worth it.
scShort: Down year for the role player
Key forward who scores best when rucking (116 from 74% CBAs), but he wont be doing much of that at the Pies
Key position player who has struggled for games at multiple clubs and I doubt it will change at a 3rd
A shutdown medium defender was used on a wing at times in 2022, but even that didnt yield decent scores

scComment: Hobbs looked terrific in a limited role in his debut season. He finished with an average of 63 from 15% CBAs, but displayed a Fantasy game to him with a score of 93. It will be interesting to see what role Scott has for the natural midfielder, given he spent the majority of his time up forward last year. If he can get his CBAs up to 30%, along with natural second year progression, we should see a nice bump in scoring from the former pick 13. I doubt that jump will be enough to make him a worthwhile selection, but forward status does keep him on the radar.
scShort: Will hope to spend more time in the middle where he showed enough to suggest he'll be a player of the future

scComment: The Carlton swingman still hasn't been able to get a good run at footy since moving from Adelaide. He looked to have settled as an intercept defender and looked great in the preseason, scoring 100 from limited game time in the AAMI. However, a bad hamstring injury in Round 2 saw him miss the next 16 matches, something that has seemed to have happened to him throughout his career. He returned to average 74 in the same role in the last 5 games, taking 28% of the kick-ins. If he can have a decent run at it, I think he can average 75-85, which is a nice bump from his price of 61, but not enough to consider starting with.
scShort: Injury prone swingman has settled into an intercept role and should push the 75-85 mark this year if fit

scComment: After moving to defence in 2021, Laverde has become a regular for the Bombers, playing every game since. His scoring output has remained in the mid-60s, so he remains irrelevant in SuperCoach.
scShort: Key defender with limited scoring

scComment: After just 4 games in 6 seasons, Hinge played 17 in 2022 as a tall wingman and mobile defender. He showed some nice flashes, but with an average of 68, I doubt hell come into SuperCoach relevance.
scShort: Got his chance on a wing and half back but scoring seems limited
Scores okay for a small forward but limited in that role

scComment: After having one of the most SuperCoach-friendly roles in 2021 where he did what he wanted in the backline to average 108, Ziebell regressed hard in 2022 as he moved to a role in the forward line. He's shown he can play multiple roles across the ground and there's no doubting his commitment to the team, but at 32, I think we've seen the best of him in real life and in SuperCoach.
scShort: Not sure what role Clarko will give him but it won't be the one from 2021 so ignore the discount

scComment: It took until Round 23 for Goater to debut but when he did he looked great, using his athletic rebounding skills to score 83. He's one we wish didn't debut so he'd be basement price this season, but priced at 35, he's still very cheap. If he looks good in the preseason and there aren't many other rookie defenders available, then you certainly could pay up.
scShort: Looked great in his 1 game but now a premium rookie price

scComment: From such a promising start, Day has had a frustrating few years in the AFL. The lightly-built former first round pick looked at home in his debut season, averaging 72 through 11 matches and was incredibly composed under pressure. We didn't see much of him in his second season due to injury, however he did score 122 and 112 in 2 of his 5 matches. I was hopeful for a big leap last season but it never happened, missing the first 2 rounds for fitness and then averaging just 66 points for the remainder. Hawthorn's defence is very stacked for distribution (Sicily, Scrimshaw, Jiath, Bramble) and Day took a backseat. I'm hoping with a full preseason under his belt, Day can return to form and look more like the player I had earmarked to one day be a top 6 defender.
scShort: Hoping for a bounce back after a few down seasons following a promising debut

scComment: The 31-year-old still has a knack of kicking goals, averaging 2 in return from playing just the 1 game the year prior. He's now at the Lions where he should see more looks than he did at the struggling Hawks, but at his age and role I'd say he'll top out around the 80 mark.
scShort: Should see more looks at the Lions but doubt he'll average much over 80
Scoring limited in the small forward role
18 matches after being delisted was impressive but might find it tough now full strength
Returned from a broken leg to play 20 matches but hes a shutdown defender

scComment: A sickening ankle injury cut his season to 12 games. Sounds like he should be fine for Round 1. Highly rated, a beautiful kick and found his spot on a half back flank, its just hard to see him becoming a relevant SuperCoach player this season.
scShort: Returning from an ankle injury and might need time before he hits his straps

scComment: The number 9 pick of the 2020 draft has played an impressive 38 games in his first 2 seasons, providing some x-factor around goal and in the air. Hes been tested in the middle at times and looked comfortable, scoring his season high 109 when he had 50% CBAs. The Bombers have a few who run through there, but I think well see more of Perkins in 2023. Hes not cheap enough for me to consider, but with his forward status hes worth keeping an eye on.
scShort: A watch on his CBAs in preseason as he looks a player and forward status makes him relevant

scComment: For a key position player, Riccardi's marking ability means he is capable of some decent Fantasy scoring. However, he was used more as a forward last year where he doesnt score as well. Still yet to lock down a position in their best 22, hes not an option this season.
scShort: Still yet to lock down a position in their best 22

scComment: A fringe midfielder had every chance to succeed in his 4th season given the injuries at West Coast, however he failed to deliver, averaging 59 from 44% CBAs. He might struggle for games with a healthy list this season.
scShort: Yet to look a scorer and might struggle with stars returning

scComment: Higgins has always been on the radar of Fantasy coaches following his monster junior scores which were likened to Fantasy great Tom Rockliff. After being limited to a small forward role with minimal Fantasy impact at Richmond, he arrived at the Saints at the end of 2020 and was flagged for some midfield opportunities, music to all Fantasy coaches' ears. However, this has never eventuated, and he didnt have a single CBA last year. He's always worth monitoring, but there's no way you can start with him based on what weve seen.
scShort: The junior stud has been limited to a small forward role at AFL level and hard to see that changing

scComment: Draper finally has a full run at it in 2022, playing all 22 matches after a tough run of injuries and getting himself AFL ready. However, he only managed 72 points from 69% CBAs. Judging from his scoring to date, it's hard to see him making an impact in SuperCoach.
scShort: First full season but didn't show enough of a SuperCoach game

scComment: Rankine finds himself at Adelaide after 3 years at Gold Coast where he established himself as a dangerous small forward. There's talk of him running through the middle for the Crows, who do lack a bit of excitement amongst Laird, Berry, Crouch and Schoenberg, but I can't see him suddenly bursting into Fantasy relevance.
scShort: Talk of mid-time at the Crows, but I'll have to see it to believe it

scComment: Doedee has been a decent scorer for a tall defender on the back of his elite intercept marking ability, averaging over 80 3 times from 2018 to 2021. He was down last year and took a back seat to Jordan Dawson, dropping his average to 77. Thats 8 points below his best, but with Dawson still there I doubt hell get back to the 80s.
scShort: Dropped his scoring with Dawson taking over

scComment: Zurhaar is a bash and crash forward who is a powerful athlete and shares some (very minor) similarities with Petracca. A move to the midfield could be on the cards one day, but I don't think it will be anytime soon so he's not an option in SuperCoach.
scShort: Strong forward who unless the unlikely midfield move happens, will remain around the 60-mark
Very exciting player to watch, but like most of his team mates, doesn't generate a lot of points under the current game style

scComment: Wehr was recruited as a mature age running defender to fill the void of Heath Shaw retiring and Zac Williams' departure. He finally got his chance in 2022 and was used on a wing, where his neat kicking skills were on display. In terms of SuperCoach though, he's now a mid-only with an awkward price point, so he's not relevant in the game this season.
scShort: Debuted as a wingman but now mid-only at an awkward price
His 71 in 2020 was an outlier, expect 50-50 from the gun small forward going forward

scComment: Played 12 matches and proved to be a strong hit-out ruckman, but there is a bit of competition there at Hawks with Lynch and Meek vying for the number 1 role.
scShort: Bit of competition there at Hawks with Lynch and Meek vying for the number 1 role

scComment: Haynes had one of his worst outputs in 2022, in both real life and in SuperCoach. It's always hard to rely on defenders who generate a lot of their possessions through intercepts as they don't always come and often the opposition tries to lead them away from the ball. He was also thrown forward at times. He's only 30, so he should be able to bounce back in the right role and system. His best is a long way off what he's priced at, but I wouldn't be buying into that value on what I saw last year.
scShort: A long way off his best in 2023 but always hard to rely on interceptors
General defender who doesn't generate enough SuperCoach points to be relevant

scComment: After 9 games in 3 seasons, West finally got his chance in 2022 and calved out a nice role as a small pressure forward. West was a highly touted inside midfielder as a junior, but with the depth of the midfield at the Dogs, he looks like he's going to continue in the forward role. While that's the case, he won't be a factor in SuperCoach.
scShort: Found a spot as a small forward but unlikely he'll move into the middle anytime soon

scComment: Cox played 18 games last season in an important forward/ruck role and looked a favourite of McRaes. With McStay arriving, I think he'll take that forward/ruck role and we might not see as much of Cox in 2023.
scShort: McStay might take the forward/ruck role and we won't see as much of Cox

scComment: Former pick 8 is now at North where he'll likley play as a shut down defender. Outside of his under 18s season where he had a run in the midfield, he hasn't shown enough to suggest he's going to be a SuperCoach option
scShort: New team, same shut down role

scComment: Super impressive debut season from the speedy midfielder. He played a few roles, from forward, wing and even inside mid, and looked good in all. Mid-only this year rules him out, but one to watch for the future.
scShort: Looks a player of the future but mid-only rules him out this year
A broken foot kept Ceglar to 2 games at his new club, but Stanley was the preferred in finals so he might find it tough again
32, small forward for a struggling team - not what you want to see in your team

scComment: Long has been around for a while without cementing himself in the 22 at St Kilda. He played a career high 18 games last season and now finds himself on the Gold Coast. He finished the season at half back and looked really damaging with his ball use and straight line running, averaging 84 in his last 5. Hes been earmarked for the same role at the Suns where I think that 84 average is achievable over a full season. Priced at 64, its almost enough to be a decent mid-priced starting squad selection for some cash gen and scoring in the early rounds. Keep an eye on him in the preseason.
scShort: A move to GC and if he can keep the role and scoring from his last 5, he could be a decent mid-priced defender
Genuine role player up forward for the Suns
Moved back to the forward line after a year on the wing explains the drop in scoring
32 years old and hasn't played a full season in 6 years, SuperCoach days are over

scComment: Back-to-back 20 game seasons, Webster shows flashes of decent SuperCoach scoring when he gets on the end of a few plus-sixes in the backline, however he's never taken it to the next level and become a decent option.
scShort: Role player in defence for the Saints

scComment: After looking the goods in his debut season, Bianco played 10 games in his second, reducing his average by 8 points to 44. His average was impacted by being the sub on a few occasions and still yet to cement his spot in the 22. Regardless, he's not going to be a SuperCoach option until/if he ever moves into a full-time mid role.
scShort: Still yet to cement his spot in the Pies' 22
Lock-down defender didn't see a bump at the Roos despite more ball being back there

scComment: Williams has always teased with a bit of a SuperCoach game about him, averaging 80 in 2 of his 5 seasons while playing as a defender. His role was more defensive last year than it was in the past, and it resulted in a 17-point reduction in scoring. He could return to scores in the 80s, however it's unlikely based on 3 of his last 4 seasons.
scShort: Has potential and scored well in the past, but 2 of last 3 low seasons makes it tough
Talented medium forward who doesn't look a scorer

scComment: Flanders was taken pick 11 in the 2019 draft alongside fellow Suns' top draftees Rowell and Anderson. However, he's certainly yet to make as much of an impact as those other two picks. He dominated at reserve level, averaging 104 AFL Fantasy points, so the talent is still there. He played just 9 game in 2022, so he's still yet to cement his spot in the team. At $256,300, he could be worth a look if he gets a midfield role in the preseason and puts up numbers like he did at VFL level. But that's unlikely.
scShort: VFL scoring a good sign for the former first rounder but yet to establish himself at AFL level

scComment: Foley arrived at West Coast with some great numbers in his under-age years but he's yet to show it at senior level. He's been forced to take a defensive role when playing seniors and at reserve level, which led to him averaging 55 points from 16 games. He had every chance to breakout last year with the injuries at West Coast and it didnt happen, so I doubt well see it this season.
scShort: Big numbers in juniors but unable to replicate it at AFL level
Unless the former top 2 pick transitions into a ruckman, won't be a Fantasy relevant player

scComment: A back up ruck to Draper that has impressed at reserves level. He won the VFL Best and Fairest for the Bombers in 2021 and averaged 87 and 89 AFL Fantasy points the last 2 years, showing his potential. Draper is the clear number one man at Essendon, so opportunities are likely to be limited again.
scShort: Back up ruck to Draper with some decent VFL numbers

scComment: The ruckman played a career high 18 games in his first season at Brisbane after struggling for games during his career at Geelong. He played backup to the Big O and looked great at times in a forward/ruck role. Hes always been a decent scorer with the right opportunity, as shown by his 91 and 96 AFL Fantasy averages in the last 2 VFL seasons and 112 from 85% CBAs when Big O missed last year. However, I doubt he'll get the chance to play as the sole ruck while Big O is healthy.
scShort: Scores well when solo but I doubt he'll get the chance while Big O is healthy
Key defender who is unlikely to play this season

scComment: Became a regular in 2022, playing 22 matches as a hard running forward. The role isnt great for SuperCoach scoring though.
scShort: Small forward role not great for Fantasy
The 2021 mid-season draft pick has played most games since, but as a low scoring wingman
Returned to defence from a tagging role but still not a Fantasy scorer
Lost his spot in the team last season and even if he does play, he's more of a role player
Breakout season for the key forward, but only resulted in 73 post bye
Far from the player who averaged 87 in 2017, now scores like a regular key forward
Hard working half forward but a role player for the Dons
Star key defender in real life and scores okay in SC, but a fair way off the top 6
More of a 55-65 key forward these days

scComment: Macdonald entered the comp with a reputation of being a high production midfielder who is effective at stoppages and works hard defensively. He obviously impressed as he debuted in Round 1 and went on to play 19 matches. He was initially used as a small forward but progressed to play as a tagger, performing a number of shut down jobs on some of the leagues best runners. He maintained his forward status for 2023 and with the departures at the Hawks, there's a chance he gets his go inside where he excelled as a junior. At his awkward price, it's not someone you'd be starting with this season, but his 121 average in his draft year means you should always keep an eye on him.
scShort: Big junior numbers but was used as a forward/tagger in his debut season, might get his chance this year with all the departures
A very good footballer but scoring will be limited in his small forward role

scComment: Throughout his career, Wingard has had periods of great scoring in a SuperCoach friendly midfield role. 117 in the last 5 of 2021, 103 in the second half of 2018 and 102 through 10 games in 2017. However, as a small forward, he scores like any other small forward, not very well. In 2022, Wingard saw just 21% CBAs, like his other veteran Hawk teammates, well down on prior seasons. He didnt go on a 100 averaging stretch, which means hes priced at 64, the cheapest he's been since his debut season. If the forward role remains, theres a bit of value there but not enough to commit to. However, if he looks to be the one to take up the midfield slack from Mitchell and OMeara leaving, then he should be on your radar for Round 1. FWIW, the way Sam Mitchell coached last season, I dont expect Wingard to get the 50%+ CBAs required.
scShort: A down year and now as cheap as he's been since his debut season, will he see more mid time following the departures?
The key defender played a career high 19 games due to the injuries at the Blues and scored typical of a key defender

scComment: Lynch moved from Collingwood to the Hawks in search of more opportunities, yet could only manage 7 games in his first season there. He battled with injury and then found himself behind Reeves in the ruck. The Hawks have added Meek to their ruck group in the offseason who appears to be the leader of the 3, meaning Lynch might find it tough for opportunities again in 2023. Hes averaged 90 AFL Fantasy points at VFL level for the past 2 seasons which is decent enough, I just think it will be hard for him.
scShort: Battling with Meek and Reeves for a spot, so he could find it hard again

scComment: Fritsch had a career low Fantasy averaging in 2023, averaging 66 points for the season. He plays as a small forward and his higher scoring seasons he had stints on the wing and half back, which explains the decline. He'll be limited to a 70 average while in the forward role at the Dees.
scShort: Limited to a 70 average while in the forward role

scComment: Behind O'Brien in the pecking order and the Crows have always preferred to play the one ruck. He did average a massive 112 AFL Fantasy points in the SANFL last year, following his 105 in 2019. He's certainly AFL ready, I just doubt he'll get the opportunity again.
scShort: Big VFL numbers but still behind O'Brien
Just the 5 games last season as the Dogs look to have moved passed him
Not quite a key position player, but plays tall and scores like one
Emerging key forward could breakout in real life this season, but his role means that won't be in SuperCoach

scComment: Out of all the 2020 draftees, I was most impressed with Powells first season, which makes his 2022 even more disappointing. The former pick 13 averaged 68 in his first season after having 35 disposals per game in SANFL Under-18s in his draft year and I earmarked him to breakout in 2022. He went on to play 18 games at an average of 56 in his second season, with less midfield time (16% CBAs down from 30%) and looked a shadow of the promising first year player. An extra preseason and new coach could see him bounce back and his forward status keeps him relevant for 2023. Hes not one Id start with, but hes worth watching to see if last year was just a blip.
scShort: Disappointing second season after an impressive debut year, hopefully he can recapture that form under the new coach
A reliable defender for the Suns, though unlikely to average much over 70 in this role
A restrictive small defender not in a SuperCoach friendly role
101 VFL average but yet to cement a spot in the Saints team
Never been an accumulator of the football, illustrated by his best career season being 70 in 13 seasons

scComment: The pick 1 in the last year's midseason draft played 4 matches in his debut season at a 63 average. He averaged 96 AFL Fantasy points at NAB League level and 67 in the WAFL, but the talk during the midseason draft and even at the 2022 National Draft was that he would've gone first round if available in it. His tackling impressed, averaging 7.5 a game which is elite numbers, and he got decent opportunity with 51% CBAs. West Coast have a few back from injury this season so Im not sure what role Culley will play and at mid-only hes not an option for this season.
scShort: Strong tackling mid impressed last season but unsure what his role will be in a full strength West Coast line-up
Brilliant return from the former number 1 pick, but his full back role isn't a SuperCoach-friendly one

scComment: Spargo is a regular at the Dees, playing 49 games in the last 2 seasons. He's currently limited to a small forward role, which isn't SuperCoach friendly. He may one day progress into the midfield, but it's an extremely hard midfield to break into at Melbourne.
scShort: Important small forward for the Dees, not for SuperCoach
A gun full back of the comp but not relevant in SuperCoach
Just 9 games last year after 22 the year before, the small forward will be on the fringe again

scComment: The former pick 28 played 7 games in his debut season an impressed with his kicking skills and speed. He might be one for the future, but he'll likely need a bit of time before being a regular midfielder.
scShort: Impressed in his debut season but will need time before being a regular midfielder
Yet to match his brilliant debut season and with mid-only, it's not worth punting on the bounce back
The developing ruck had his chance in 2023 with no NicNat and only managed a 55 from 52% CBAs
Tall wing yet to show he can accumulate the footy

scComment: The son of Peter and younger brother of Trent, Jase played 7 games in his debut season in defence and impressed. Port Adelaide's defence is strong and it might be hard to get a regluar spot this season, but he certainly looks one for the future.
scShort: Impressed in 7 games last year but hard to trust in 2nd season
Key defender on the fringe of the best 22
Dropped 25 points last season so there's some upside if he returns to 94, but hard to trust key defenders in SuperCoach
JK retiring may help, but 56 from 19 last year isn't SuperCoach worthy
Fringe key defender was better past season but still doesn't have a decent enough scoring role
Promising running defender, but behind a few for usage so he might need some time before we see him at his best

scComment: Maginness played a career high 16 games in 2022 as a wingman and tagger. He has elite running capacity which allowed him to shut down some of the best runners in the AFL, but its not a role that leads to scoring. At mid-only, hes not relevant this season.
scShort: Hard running wing/tagger isn't much of a scorer himself

scComment: The mature-aged ruckman played 6 games in 2022 after 5 in 2021. With the arrival of Lobb and English hitting his peak, we might not see much more of him in 2023.
scShort: Unlikley to feature with Lobb backing up English
Now at the Dees but unlikely to change his scoring output nor place in the 22
Intercept defender better in real life than SuperCoach
Pressure forward out of consideration in Fantasy
Small forward not what you want in SuperCoach
Scored best in past when rucking and given how good he was up forward last year, that won't happen
Role player at Port in defence, not a scorer

scComment: Thomas' 2022 season was as disappointing as I've seen. The former top 10 pick was heading into his fourth season coming off a career best season of 84, 95 in second half and 110 in his last 5. With CBAs increasing in line, and low TOG, he ticked all the boxes for a breakout. He instead went down in scoring by 31 points per game and down in CBAs, even finding himself playing VFL football for a lot of it. A fresh start with a new coach is a blessing and it sounds like he's been training as a half back in the preseason and match sim. He's one of the bigger preseason watches as if he can even get back to his 2021 level of scoring, he'll be a worthwhile pick.
scShort: Hoping for a bounce back after a disappointing 2022 - 95 in 2nd half of 2021 the hope!
Gun key defender and despite 37 points less than his best, not one for SuperCoach
Can play forward, back and ruck and it looks like he's settled in the least SuperCoach-friendly role, defence

scComment: Bruce returned from an ACL last season and struggled to get going, averaging just 37 points. With the plethora of talls up forward at the Dogs, Bruce is said to be trialled down back, which I think would be a great move for Bruce and the Dogs. Regardless, he's priced as a rookie at $161k, or 29 points. Even if he gets back to his mid-60 scores as a forward, he'd prove a great cash cow. And I think it could be better if the defender-move works.
scShort: Struggled in his return from an ACL and said to be trialled in defence which makes him an option at that price

scComment: Meek has been stuck behind Darcy at Freo but developing well in the WAFL. He averaged 103 Fantasy points for Peel last season, up from 95 the year prior. He moved to the Hawks in the offseason where there is every chance of him being their number 1 ruck. Reeves and Lynch are currently there vying for that role and both are pretty good, which means it's not a sure thing Meek takes the number 1 spot. If he gets the nod, I can see him putting up 95+, which would give some nice cash gen while the other rucks settle. However, priced at 78, any less than 95 would make him a failed pick. With Hayes going down at the Saints and the concern Marshall might be forward, Meek at R2 is becoming a more realistic move.
scShort: Big chance to be Hawks number 1 guys which could see 95+ scoring based on his WAFL form

scComment: Was drafted as one of the premier midfielders of the 2020 draft, however has had to settle with a forward role for the time being given the midfield depth at the Giants. He now finds himself at Geelong, who despite being the reigning premiers, theyre not super deep in the mids. He should get his chance to play more midfield which would be a boost to his scoring. He did get 37% CBAs in the first half of last year and only managed 67, so I don't think we're going to see high scoring from him. Keep an eye on him given his talent, forward status and more mid time, but I doubt he'll make an impact in SuperCoach this season.
scShort: Should get more midfield opportunities at the Cats but going by his scoring to date, I doubt he'll boost his score enough
A role player in defence for Freo who has only managed 13 games in 2 years

scComment: Fogarty has been on the radar since he was drafted after his elite junior numbers, highlighted by a 124 AFL Fantasy average in the NAB League. However, managed just 3 games last year for the Blues after struggling for opportunities at the Cats earlier in his career. It's likely he'll struggle for opportunities again, but if he is named, he's worth a look based on his price and junior scores.
scShort: Just 3 games last season and might find it tough again for opportunities, but if he does, he's worth a look based on price and junior scores
Small forward played 17 games last season but scoring is limited

scComment: Ralphsmith played 13 games last season in a half back role and looked good. However, it only yielded an average of 53, and with the likelihood of Short moving back to defence, Ralphsmith might be on the fringe in 2023.
scShort: The likelihood of Short moving back to defence, Ralphsmith might be on the fringe in 2023
Still behind Preuss and Flynn for the starting ruck spot
Found a role in defence but not a scoring one

scComment: There's no doubting Coleman-Jones has talent, however he's yet to really crack it at AFL level. Not even a move to the Kangaroos provided more job security, with just 10 games last season at an average of 53. He continued to dominate at lower level, averaging 104 at VFL level after 115 the year prior and 116 in his draft year. Those scores came from playing predominantly in the ruck and at AFL level, he plays as a key forward. If he's ever handed to keys to be the number 1 ruck then he could be worth a look, but that's an unlikely scenario.
scShort: Yet to cement his spot at AFL level despite but VFL scores
78 in 2020 the outlier, he's been a mid-50s guy his whole career
A reliable defender but not a scorer

scComment: Worpel has had two poor seasons in a row after bursting onto the scene. He averaged 97 in just his 2nd season, looking like becoming a star mid of the comp. However, he's dropped in average every season since, bottoming out last year to average just 56. He played just 46% in the midfield and certainly didn't suit the outside role he was forced to play. Mitchell and O'Meara's departures mean there are CBAs up for grabs at the Hawks. But what I've seen since Sam Mitchell has taken over doesn't give me confidence that Worpel will receive any of these. Mitchell doesn't want Worpel winning outside ball and demands him to play a role that isn't great for his SuperCoach scoring. He has to be a preseason watch regardless based on past scoring history and his price, 41 points less than his average in his 2nd season. A consistent midfield role would make but a decent midpriced option, I just think Sam Mitchell will give more time to Ward, McDonald, Newcombe and Moore meaning Worpel might not get that bump in CBAs.
scShort: A big fall from his early career scores and could get his chance to bounce back with the departures of key mids
Role player for the Tigers who lost his spot in the 22 at times last seasons

scComment: Rachele burst out of the blocks in 2022, kicking 5 goals on debut and 12 after 5 rounds. He slowed as the season went on, as many rookies do, but certainly showed enough to suggest hes going to be a star of the future. The former pick 6 has been floated as a possible midfielder this season and I think well see him used in there at times as he offers something their current mids dont. However, I doubt well see him get the 50% required for him to score well enough in SuperCoach to consider in our teams.
scShort: Talk of more midfield time but I think he'll predominantly be a small forward again this season which isn't great for SuperCoach

scComment: Arrived as a mature age (26) SSP selection after being SANFL's premier key forward in recent years averaging, averaging 128 AFL Fantasy points in 2021. He didn't disappoint, scoring 127 on debut and I had to double take if it was him of Marshall. Unfortunately, he did his knee in Round 6 and missed the rest of the season. He was set for an early season return, however hurt his foot at training and is now set to miss the first part of the year. He was never a starting pick himself, but with King also missing the early rounds, the likelihood of Marshall having to play forward has increased.
scShort: Loved his 4 games last season and unfortunately he's out for the start of 2023 which could have implications for Marshall
Plays as a speedy small forward and certainly hasn't looked a scorer to date
Tall swingman whose scoring hasnt moved much with a change of position and club
A key position player who would score a bit higher if he kicked straighter, but not enough to make an impact
Returned from a second ACL to play 15 games and show some good signs, just not enough for SuperCoach
Tall forward/ruck who is yet to cement his spot in the Swans' 22
Developing key forward / backup ruckman also yet to cement his spot in the team

scComment: Tucker has moved to North after 7 seasons with Freo. He never averaged more than 73 at Freo, playing multiple roles from half back, wing, inside mid and forward last season. He dominated in the WAFL to average 99 AFL Fantasy points last season, so he can score when in the right role. I'm not sure his role will be in the midfield at the Roos, but if it is in the preseason, then he's worth a look as a mid-priced forward.
scShort: Should get more opportunities at North and if that means midfield then he's worth a look at that price
Might see more games on the wing with Hunter leaving, but career best average of 58 and just 59 in VFL last year isn't a great sign
Former pick 16 playing as a small forward and unless an (unlikely) move to the mids occurs, he's not going to be a factor
A junior stud who plays as a role player in defence at the Dees and down the pecking order for distribution
Small forward broke out last season but still only managed 56 points in the role
14 games last season in defence but not an accumulator of the ball
Looks a player with his clean hands but doesn't win enough football to be relevant in this game
A nice intercept marker, but a genuine full back and not a player you want in your team
Key defender in and out of the side

scComment: Martin showed a heap of promise early days but has failed to go on with it. He bottomed out last season, averaging 54 points per game, which is 29 points below his best. Up until the 2 seasons, he was a mid-to-low 80s guy, so you'd have to think he could get back to that level and that would be enough to make him a worthwhile selection. But it would be hard to select him based on the last 2 seasons.
scShort: Dropped off the last 2 seasons and despite his discount to career best, he's hard to trust
Gun intercept defender whose was down last season but even if he returns to 89, its not enough
4 games in 3 years at the Dees, might get more chances at the Dogs and at that price he's worth a shot if named
A solid key forward at almost 2 goals a game, but not a scorer in this game

scComment: Got his chance last season with Lycett out, playing the 7 games to average 73. He's done his time in the SANFL, averaging almost 90 AFL Fantasy points for 3 seasons, so I expected him to score a bit better than he did. Port opted to play no recognised ruck at times, using Finlayson and Dixon over Hayes, which isn't a great sign. Lycett is back so I think we might see Hayes go back to the SANFL.
scShort: Only 7 games in a year Lycett missed a chunk isn't a great sign

scComment: In a down year for West Coast, Hough was one of the few shining lights. He played 15 games and looked very composed with ball in hand. He should get his chances again while West Coast are developing and improve again, but I doubt it will be by enough to make him relevant.
scShort: Impressive debut season but unlikely to make an impact this year
Mature aged rookie played 15 games on debut, but in a small forward role, not the midfield role where he averaged 100 AF in the VFL
Key defender who excels in one-on-one contests but doesn't have much of an offensive game

scComment: Robertson was one of the most hyped rookies in SuperCoach when he was drafted, following his elite scoring in his draft year; 113 AFL Fantasy average in the National Championships (ranked 1) and 120 average in WAFL colts (also ranked 1). He hasnt done a heap at AFL level in his first 3 seasons, playing just the 7 games last season for a 65 average. His 104 in the VFL shows he still has it, but it might be much the same for Robertson this season as Dunkley puts him another player behind for midfield opportunities.
scShort: Junior gun but might be much the same this year as Dunkley puts him another player behind for midfield opportunities

scComment: Saints look like they got a steal with Windhager, taken pick 47 of the 2021 draft. He looked as comfortable as many of the top picks, playing multiple roles including as a tagger inside. I think he's got the attributes to make it, but in his second season at that price, it's unlikely he'll be relevant this season unless he plays as ball winning mid.
scShort: Impressive debut season and one for the future, but unlikely to be this year

scComment: Campbell is dealing with a sore achilles which is likely to delay his start to the season. The relevance comes due to the potential of him playing as the main ruck and Rowan Marshall forward, which us coaches don't want. Campbell did average 112 AFL Fantasy points at VFL level last season but I I doubt he'll ever get the regular number 1 role at the Saints.
scShort: Depth ruck dealing with a sore achilles which is likely to delay his start to the season
A small forward with a bit of energy about him, not one for the SuperCoach scorers though
Struggled to cement his spot in his 6 seasons
The veteran medium forward has been on the fringe of the Demons' 22 for a while now
Defender without much attacking side to his game
Loved the look of this mid-season draftee with his elite kicking skills, however cant see him taking the leap from this price
Mid-only and no CBAs rules him out
Tall forward who doesn't score enough to consider
Key defender with a career high average of 70

scComment: It's not the first time Milera has created some buzz as a mid-priced selection in the preseason. In 2018 he averaged 93 in the last 5 games which made him a popular pick in 2019. In 2019, he started strong, averaging 91 in the first 5 before getting injured and interrupting his season. Unfortunately, it's been the same old story for Milera, who has more time off the park than on. He played 12 games last season and certainly looked like he'd missed a lot of football, averaging just 58 for the season in mixed roles. He enters 2023 with a full preseason under his belt and the word is that he's been moved back to his favourable half back position. He's a preseason watch for both role and confidence, because if he can average 85+, which he's shown he can, he'll prove a great mid-priced selection. But comes with the obvious injury, role and spot in 22 risks.
scShort: Talk of a move back to half back where he's gone 80+ before, if he can do that again he'll be a good pick - massive IF though
Promising key forward but not one for SuperCoach
Averaged 91 AF in VFL after 100 the year before, but unlikely to get a decent role at AFL level
Talented forward now at Geelong where he could see more games but won't score enough
Plays the defensive forward role super well for the Pies, just not a role for Fantasy
Failed to live up to expectations after being taken with pick 6, the change of environment to West Coast has so far failed to reignite his career
Showed great signs in his 1st season as an intercept mark and tall forward, but won't be in Fantasy calcs this year
Mid-season draftee whose scores at reserve level don't jump off the page
Hard working forward who now at age 31, might find it tough to squeeze into their best 22
Has showed some nice signs, but a developing tall forward is always going to need time
Played 41 games in 2 seasons but the former top 10 pick hasn't shown much in the scoring department
Key defender who dropped 14 points due to reduced kick ins and I doubt it will go back up
Plays 2nd ruck behind Nank, which means he's in and out of the side
Drafted top 10 in 2018 as a midfielder, although limited to defence and scoring isn't there
Mature age who put up big scores at reserve level before being drafted and in the VFL last year, but doesn't play that role when at AFL level
Has tempted SuperCoachers since his 94 average in 2016, but he's dropped a long way off and proved far too inconsistent
A depth player in the forward line with a career best average of 60 from 6 seasons

scComment: Owens played 7 games in his debut season and looked the goods, showcased by a great tackling ability. He was used in a tagging role and up forward. Could be one for the future, but I doubt he'll feature in SuperCoach calculations this season.
scShort: Showed a great tackling ability but I doubt he'll feature in SuperCoach calculations this season
Mid-season draftee looked great with his hands and skills around goal, not a SuperCoach scorer though
Only 2 games in debut season, looking neat in defence, but there are plenty of them at the Dogs so might find it tough again
99 AF in SANFL, up from 67, but scoring at AFL level looks limited

scComment: Cox impressed everyone in his first season, playing 20 games at an average of 57. He dropped to just 5 games at 45 in year 2 as he continues to develop and find his role in the team. It might be a few years before we see the best of Cox.
scShort: Versatile high pick, might be a few years before we see the best of him
Lightly-built mid-season pick looked pretty good last season, but I doubt he'll become an accumulating defender
Been on the outer the past 3 seasons after being a regular goal kicker for the Suns
Solid defender but highest average over the 9 years is 67
Mid-season pick averaged 104 AF at VFL level and looked good in the AFL, but with Mitchell there might find it tougher
An accumulator at reserve level for a number of years, however he's never cemented his spot in the 22
Brilliant season and a star of the future, but tall defender not the role for scoring in SuperCoach
16 games from the former pick 1 and will continue to get better, but not as a SuperCoach asset
The versatile Kangaroo not a SuperCoach scorer
70 in 2019 was on a wing, he's now back as a key defender so ignore the discount to career high
Only 9 games in 2 seasons but he's a goal kicker, just not a scorer
Never played more than 11 games in a season, too hard to trust

scComment: Top 10 pick with monster junior numbers (109 AF in WAFL Colts), high endurance and good size. He made the step up to seniors, averaging 96 AF in the WAFL this season and had some chances at AFL level, playing 4 games. 2 of those he had less than 50% game time as sub, so his 52 average isn't the best read. I think we'll see a lot more of him this season, but it's still going to be hard to get consistent CBAs with Brayshaw, Serong, Brodie and O'Meara taking up the majority. While Freo are contending, it's unlikely they will give many minutes inside to their kids, but I can see Erasmus playing on the wing this season. Expect a nice bump in average, but it might be a year or two before we see him putting up consistent numbers worthy of SuperCoach selection.
scShort: Looks to have the attributes of a future star, just might need some time to get his chance in the contending Freo side
Taken as an overager in the 2020 rookie draft and played the majority of game but in a defensive forward role

scComment: The mature aged pick of 2021 had SuperCoaches tongues wagging after averaging 121 AF in the WAFL in his draft year. His season was delayed due to an AC injury, but he debuted in Round 7 and didn't disappoint, scoring 104. He missed the following week with COVID protocols and then never reached those heights again. Outside of his debut, I was underwhelmed by him and despite him still being 25, I think he might struggle for games in the full strength West Coast line-up. If he is a first choice mid in the preseason, there's some value at that price given what we know he can do, but he's been used on a wing at AFL level and I doubt he'll get the inside minutes.
scShort: Monster junior scores and on debut looked to be Barlow 2.0, but didn't go on with it and now unlikely to have an inside role
Only 2 matches in 2022 and with the emergence of the young Freo defenders, I doubt we see much of him this season

scComment: Campbell showed a lot of promise early as a rookie, scoring 96 in his second game. He ended up out of the side and then became injured. He played 14 games in his second season but most of them as sub. He's got a terrific kick on him and showed enough for me to think he'll be a star of the future. Priced at 46, he'll outperform that price if given the opportunities, but based on the first 2 years, he might not get enough chances.
scShort: Elite kick and has talent, but hard to see him getting enough chances this year to make him a decent pick
Key defender and certainly not a scorer
Top 10 pick but a tall key defender with a sub-50 VFL average
Developing tall defender who famously finished top 10 in AFL Fantasy Classic in 2021, not relevant himself though
Key defender and certainly not a SuperCoach scorer

scComment: Former pick 3 with huge potential, averaged 94 AF in the VFL which shows he shaped up well against the men. One for the future, but likely to remain on the outside / VFL until he fully develops.
scShort: Future star and should get more chances in 2023, he just might need some more developing before we see him ready to pop
28-year-old key defender that has a career-high average of 72
Genuine key defender

Irishman got his chance in 2022 but 55 at AFL and 56 AF in VFL doesn't look like he's going to be a scorer
Just 49 in SANFL and 39 in AFL
Vandermeer has some talent, but a career average of 50 doesn't suggest he's going to be a scorer

scComment: McLean comes into 2023 high on the watchlist. He returned from back-to-back ACL reconstructions to play in the finals, where he scored 100. This score isn't built into his price, so he's priced at a rookie-level price of 32. The mid-60-mark is what he averaged from 2019-2021 and if he returned to that level he'll made a decent level of cash and prove a worthy starting squad selection. He averaged 95 at AFL level before in 2018 as a midfielder, and in that year he was going at 111 in the first 10 games. He also averaged 96 AF in the VFL last year, so on that form he can surpass the mid-60-mark. A preseason watch, obviously any CBA action will be a bonus as a small forward role is very hard to rely on in Fantasy, but hes certainly underpriced.
scShort: Priced at 32 after missing the regular season but form in finals, VFL and 2018 suggests he can blow that price out of the park
A consistent defender for the Cats, never surpassed 60 in a season though
Injury kept him game less in 2022 and even if he bounces back to 2021 form, he'll be short of the 150k mark to be a worthwhile cash generator
Got his chance in his first season due to injuries and looked okay, but a nullifying defender who won't be a scorer
Might get more chances at the Dons, but a key forward who has never been a scorer

scComment: Sharp finished 2021 looking like he was the Suns wingman of the future, averaging 73 points per game (excluding his 5). He found it harder in 2022 though, only playing 11 games at an average of 41. He showed enough in 21 and at VFL level (110 AF average) that he can outperform that price by enough if given the opportunity. However, thats not guaranteed and the fact hes only available in the midfield, he loses a lot of appeal.
scShort: Priced well below his 2021 and VFL scoring, but yet to cement his spot and mid-only makes it tricky
Tough defender who I confuse with Moore at times such is his marking ability, but far from a scorer in SuperCoach
Played 6 games in '22 both forward and back, and while he looked more at home in defence (65 av), he doesn't look like high scorer
Natural inside mid and showed his talent with a 95, but limited to a forward role at AFL level, unlikely to score much there
I liked his 3 games but didn't appear after Leon left, might get more chances now but scoring history isn't flash
Former first rounder yet to show any signs he's going to make it

scComment: The first-round draft pick from 2019 finally debuted in 2022, playing the 5 matches. He looked pretty good in limited game time (61%) and would've learnt a lot in his 3 seasons at the Cats. He's now at Hawthorn where he should walk into their best 22 and play a decent role. That's enough to put him on the watch list, but mid-only and moderate scoring history (68 AF in draft year, 61 AF at VFL level, 54 at AFL level) will make it hard to do.
scShort: Will get his chances at the Hawks but poor scoring at lower level curbs any excitement
Has scored okay when playing as a backup ruck, but now solely a key forward (1% CBA in 22)
Talented player and VFL numbers up from prior season, but just 44 from a few CBAs at AFL level not great reading
Star defender who has put up 70s in the past, but hes purely focussed on defending now
Strong bodied defender seems a favourite at Port and was even flagged for mid-time last year, but that never happened, and he places a defensive role for the team
Promising key defender, not as a SuperCoach scorer though
Small pressure forward not in a role for scoring, so unless we see an (unlikely) midfield move under Clarko, he won't be relevant in SuperCoach
Numbers at junior level were okay, however 61 at AFL and 63 AF at VFL as a defender arent great

scComment: The mid-season draftee played 2 games in his first season but showed great signs in both of them with an 73 in 1 game and an early injury in his other. With Lycett back, I'm not sure how much we'll see Teakle, but he did provide some energy that Port have lacked in the ruck for a while. He's a bit awkwardly priced, so unless he's named sole ruck in Round 1, he won't be relevant this season.
scShort: Might struggle with Lycett back
Should get a decent role at West Coast, has averaged 70+ in the past but hard to rely on outside runners

scComment: The former top 10 pick hasn't really come on and then unfortunately did his ACL last preseason. He has attributes to be a good SuperCoach defender, a neat kick and ability to generate marks. He finished 2020 averaging above 80 in the last 5 games and that's about the mark I think he can produce at his best. He's obviously going to need some time to find his feet when he returns and it's unknown what role Ross will have for him, but if he looks fit in the preseason, he's a midpriced defender I don't mind, especially given the gap between the top 5 and the rest.
scShort: Returning from an ACL and priced well below his potential, if he looks fit in preseason you could take the punt

scComment: The former number 3 pick has always been on the radar due to his draft position, but is yet to deliver. His numbers at VFL level are getting better, but mid-only in 2023, you cant do it on exposed form.
scShort: We've been waiting for a breakout but mid-only in 2023, you cant do it on exposed form
Small forward new club but same unfavourable role
Versatile tall that can play at both ends but with 2 games last season, he's a depth player

scComment: Returning from 2 years in Ireland and should lot into his customary running defender role at the Lions, who need some pace back there. His best ever season was an 80 average, with the majority in the mid-60s. He's priced at 30, so he only needs to touch 60 again to make the cash needed to prove a worthwhile pick. As long as he's named in Round 1, he's a pretty clear selection in SuperCoach.

scShort: Has potential to be a very good key forward, but not a Fantasy one
The hard running tall forward has great hands and should play more than he did at GC last season, but won't come into Fantasy calculations
Small forward became a regular, but average of 42 sums up the role
Mid-only with a 57 AF SANFL average and 44 AFL average

scComment: After impressing in his debut season, Edwards suffered osteitis pubis for the whole of his second season, eventually ending his season early. He's highly rated internally, however at that price point for a mid-only, you're better with a lower priced rookie, unless he impresses in the preseason matches.
scShort: Interrupted 2022 and highly rated, but tough at that price and mid-only
32-yr-old full back on the rookie list, not the combo you want
Knee surgery in offseason for the defender

Versatile tall struggled for games last season and the Bombers may have moved past him
Key forward who might struggle for opportunities this year

Defender with 5 games in 3 seasons and an average of 67 AF in the SANFL

SANFL numbers reduced last season (72 AF to 64) and scoring wasn't great at AFL level

Promising tall defender will be sidelined for the start of the season
Small forward with a 51 AF VFL average and max 4 games at AFL level in a season

scComment: Emerging key forward missed the entire 2022 season due to injury. He put up 78 in just his 3rd season, showing that he will score more than the average key forward. He's priced at 38 given his missed season, which is well under what he has produced. I never like having key forwards in SuperCoach, even if they are cheap. A sub-65 average would make it a poor pick as you could get that output from a rookie for less of a price. He'd be a great pick if he can reproduce that 70+, but West Coast aren't as strong as they were then and 2 of his last 4 seasons have been sub-65 scores, so I'm out of this one.
scShort: Missed 2022 meaning he's priced at 38, well down from his best (78) but I never like key forwards in SuperCoach
Small forward who spent most of last season as sub should get more chances at GWS, but the small forward role isn't a high scoring one even with a full game
Developed as a great defender, but a 60 point average from a full season suggests he's far from a scorer
Only 2 games after 13 the season before suggest he might struggle for opportunities again
Played a far less attacking role at the Tigers, ignore the discount to career high for the 33-year-old
2 games last year and then put on the rookie list suggests the Lions may have moved past him
Great numbers in his draft year and played the 1 game on debut, mid-only and a premium rookie price doesn't make him that attractive even if named Round 1
Medium defender picked up in the 2020 mid-season draft, had AFL Fantasy averages in the 60s at VFL level up until last year's 71, so doesn't appear a scorer
Small forward showed plenty in his first season, but that still led to a 44 average such is the role
A big ball winner at the lower level, Banfield has mostly played as a defensive forward in the AFL which doesn't generate high scores, especially as sub 10 times

scComment: Former top 5 pick is still very lightly built, but showed some moments in his 4 games last season. Once developed physically, the high leaping Andrew should become a gun ruckman, but until then it looks like he's being trailed as a tall defender. He's suspended to start the season, however as he is still developing, he wouldn't have been relevant anyway.
scShort: Suspended to start the season, however as he is still developing, he wouldn't have been relevant anyway
Versatile big man has become a very reliable defender for the Giants and has also pinched hit in the ruck, but as a defender he's not going to score enough in SuperCoach
Reliable defender missed 2022 with a serious ankle injury, discounted price but needs to go over 60 to be worthwhile over a rookie which he's only just done 50% of last 4 seasons
A developing ruck prospect played 9 games in 2022 due to injures, however he still looks a few years off the level

scComment: The former pick 6 certainly hasn't come on as we all expected him to, and bottomed out last season with just 4 games at senior level. The Swans seem to have a way of getting the best out of players, so there's some home there now that he's made the switch. The 40/50s in the past certainly aren't enough to be a worthy pick, however he has an intercept marking ability that should be able to generate more SuperCoach points than he does. He did average 81 in 5 games in 2018 and anything around that mark would prove a bargain buy. He needs to get a game first, and if he is named Round 1, he could be worth a look at that price.
scShort: Hopefully gets a chance at the Swans and if they can get him back to his best he could be a great 'rookie' defender
Made the move to the Suns in 2021 in a very strange recruitment, never played more than 8 games since arriving and will unlikely be in their best team again
I liked the look of the running defender when he first started, but max average of 40 and just 12 games last season doesn't read well
Strong marking forward who only played 2 games last season and a 63 VFL AF average isn't great

scComment: Highly rated by those who have seen a lot of him. He's yet to show much to date, however he's spent most his time playing as a small forward and is tipped to play more on the wing in 2023, where he can use his elite leg speed and evasiveness. The former top 10 pick should see a bump in scoring if that eventuates, I just cant see it improving by enough based on exposed form.
scShort: Training as a wing which is better than a small forward, but I cant see him improving by enough based on exposed form
Was recruited as a hard-running midfielder, but been used as a small forward when at AFL level and hard to see him changing that

scComment: Promising key forward who showed some great signs in his limited games. I think he'll become a very good player, but young key forwards are never good Fantasy options
scShort: Young key forwards are never good SuperCoach options
Great to see Tippa back! But will need some time getting to fitness and never been a SuperCoach asset as a small forward
56 VFL AF average and 4 sub 60 seasons at AFL level sums him up

scComment: Constable was delisted from Geelong at the end of 2021 and was thrown a lifeline by Gold Coast, however he didnt see much more AFL action with just the 1 game in 2022 (as sub). Constable has been a strong VFL player over his career, averaging 100 AF last season and 111 in 2021. He averaged 80 from 7 games in 2019 at the top level (his debut year), so he can obviously find the football. It's a question on if he is best 22  Gold Coast bat deep in the midfield and hell likely find it tough again.
scShort: Great VFL numbers but has very been able to get a decent crack at AFL level, unlikely to change this season
Just 4 games last season so he comes in very cheap, yet to cement himself in the team but if he does, he could prove a decent cash generator if he gets back to high-60s
Started his career as a forward but moved to defense, however scoring and position in team still not solid
Simpson burst on the scene with a 112 in Round 6 2020, but struggled since and didn't play a game last season
